\section*{Introduction}

The nutritional status of a woman before and during pregnancy is important for a healthy pregnancy outcome. Adequate provision of nutrients, beginning in early stages of life, is crucial to ensure good physical and mental development and long-term health. Poor availability or access to food of adequate nutritional quality or the exposure to conditions that impair absorption and use of nutrients leads to undernutrition, poor vitamin and mineral status or overweight and obese may often present simultaneously. Maternal malnutrition is a key contributor to poor fetal growth, low birthweight (LBW) and short- and long-term infant morbidity and mortality.

Nutrition plays a pivotal role in determining health outcomes across the life course. ${ }^{1,5}$ In resource-poor Sub-Saharan Africa, South-Central and South-East Asia, maternal under-nutrition is highly prevalent and is recognized as a key determinant of maternal and perinatal outcomes. ${ }^{1}$, ${ }^{2}$.Adequate provision of nutrients, beginning in early stages of life, is crucial to ensure good physical and mental development and long-term health outcomes. $\underline{2}$ While obesity has historically been a condition associated with affluence, there is some evidence to suggest a shift in the burden of overweight and obesity seen across populations. Obesity and overweight have been associated with poor pregnancy outcomes ${ }^{1}$

