The intergenerational cycle of growth failure can be turned into a vicious cycle. However, Low birth weight can be prevented, even amongst undernourished women by improving their diet in quantity and quality. Nutrition in the early months of pregnancy has the greatest benefit on birth outcomes. The effects are greater if the mother is reached before the first semester of pregnancy or early into the pregnancy. Tackling anemia during adolescence and preventing or delaying teenage pregnancy may help to break the intergenerational cycle.

Increasing birth weight contributes to reduction in child growth faltering in the first 2 years of life, resulting in less stunting at two years of age. This is eventually reflected in increased adult height, improved cognitive function and intellectual development across the life-course, all associated with an increase in birth weight and a reduction in stunting.

There is often little emphasis on maternal nutrition because the priority focus has been placed on interventions that produce short-term gains in child survival. An understanding of the importance of growth and development outcomes is critical and a focus on birth weight should be strengthened. Furthermore, the importance of maternal nutrition for mothers' own health and development must be emphasized.

\section*{Epidemiology}

Both low body mass index (BMI) and short stature are highly prevalent among women of reproductive age in low- and middle-income countries. This leads to poor fetal development, increased risk of complications in pregnancy, and the need for assisted delivery ${ }^{2}$.

In some countries in South-Central Asia, more than 10\% of women aged 15-49 years are shorter than 145 cm . In Sub-Saharan Africa, South-Central and South-Eastern Asia, more than 20\% of women have a BMI less than $18.5 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{2}$. ${ }^{1,2}$ Recent trends show an increased proportion of women starting pregnancy with a $\mathrm{BMI}>30 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{m}^{2}$, leading to increased risk of complications in pregnancy and delivery as well as heavier birth weight and increased risk of obesity in children. $34.3 \%$ of females in Kenya are overweight with a BMI of above $25 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{M}^{2}$ while $11.1 \%$ are obese with a BMI of above $30 \mathrm{~kg} / \mathrm{M}^{2} \stackrel{\perp, 2,14}{ }$

Globally, iron-deficiency anemia affects $30 \%$ women of reproductive age ( 468 million), and $42 \%$ of pregnant women ( 56 million). Maternal anemia is associated with reduced birth weight and increased risk of maternal mortality. In Kenya, the prevalence of anaemia among women of reproductive age is $27.2 \%$ out of which, $38.2 \%$ are pregnant. ${ }^{\underline{1}, 2,14}$

Every year an estimated 13 million children are born of pregnancies complicated by intrauterine growth restriction. Another 20 million children are born with low birth weight. In Kenya, 8\% of newborns are low birthweight with regional disparities ranging from $13 \%$ in the coastal region to $4 \%$ in Nyanza. Low birth weight babies have a greater risk of morbidity and mortality and are more likely to develop non-communicable diseases, such as diabetes and hypertension, later in life. ${ }^{2,15}$

