\section*{General Nutrition Requirements in Pregnancy}

Indicators of good nutritional status during pregnancy include:
- Weight gain between 11.5-16 kg during pregnancy
- Hemoglobin level $\geq \mathrm{IIg} / \mathrm{dl}$
- Absence of clinical signs of micronutrient deficiencies

\section*{Energy and Protein Requirements in Pregnancy}

During pregnancy, the needs for energy and protein are increased in order to meet the demands for adequate maternal gestational weight gain, as well as the growth and development of the fetus. ${ }^{3}, 5$ Extra energy is needed to sustain the increased basal metabolic rate and there is normal accumulation of fat as the energy reserves. ${ }^{5}$ Maternal stores of nitrogen are increased in pregnancy, hence increased need for protein, especially those with low BMI <18.5.

An increase of protein from $0.8 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{kg} \mathrm{BW}$ per day to $\mathrm{l} . \mathrm{l} \mathrm{g} / \mathrm{kg}$ BW per day is required to facilitate the physiological changes of pregnancy, including: Tissue growth, nitrogen balance, fetal growth and development, enlargement of mammary glands, uterus and placenta, increased circulating blood volume and plasma proteins, formation of amniotic fluid, reserves for labor, delivery and lactation. There is evidence that providing adequate energy and protein during pregnancy improves fetal growth and may reduce the risk of stillbirth, low birthweight and infants born small for gestational age even among under nourished women. A proper dietary balance is necessary to ensure sufficient intake for adequate growth without drawing from the mother's own tissues to maintain her pregnancy. It is recommended that the woman consume one small extra meal equivalent to 300 Kcal . Further, meals should be drawn from at least five of the ten food groups daily. ${ }^{5,13}$

\section*{Micronutrient Requirements for Pregnant and Lactating Mothers}

\section*{$\underline{2}, \underline{3}, \underline{5}$}
- During pregnancy, there is an increased need for micronutrient requirements. All major and trace minerals and vitamins have a role in maternal health.
- The pregnant and lactating mothers need extra folic acid and vitamin B I2 due to the great increase in blood volume /cells and the rapid growth of the fetus.
- Iron demands increase as the body conserves more than usual during pregnancy and the growing fetus draws on maternal iron stores.
- Minerals involved in building the skeleton- calcium, magnesium and phosphorus are also in great demand. A non-pregnant adult woman would require 800 mg calcium, 280 mg magnesium and 800 mg of phosphorus. In pregnancy, these requirements are increased.
- Micronutrients are required by the body for multiple physiological functions, including: production of enzymes \& hormones; formation of brain cells; regulation of physical growth \& development; regulation of the immune system and reproductive system; and for optimal functioning of the muscular and the nervous system.

The following micronutrients play a critical role in pregnancy.

\section*{Iron}

Pregnant women require additional iron for their own nutritional needs and for the developing foetus. Daily oral elemental iron is recommended for pregnant women to prevent maternal anaemia, puerperal sepsis, low birthweight and preterm birth. It is essential for many enzymes
that are required for metabolism of glucose and fatty acids. It plays a vital role in the body's immune system as well as in the synthesis of hormones and neurotransmitters. Women of reproductive age and infants have the highest need for iron.

Extra iron is needed for hemoglobin synthesis during pregnancy; the recommended daily dose in pregnancy is $60 \mathrm{mg} /$ day . Inadequate iron intake, resulting in iron deficiency, is the commonest cause of anemia.

\section*{Consequences of Iron Deficiency Anemia}
- Anemic women are more likely to die from Post-Partum Hemorrhage (PPH) and in the postpartum period
- Severe anemia can precipitate heart failure or circulatory shock at the time of labor, delivery and post-partum
- Anemic women are also more susceptible to puerperal infection

\section*{Risk factors for iron deficiency anemia include:}
- Inadequate consumption, or low intake of heme iron
- High consumption of staple foods with low bio available iron
- Inadequate intake of foods that enhance iron absorption from diet, such as Vitamin C containing foods
- Consumption of foods high in phytate or phenolic compounds that inhibit iron absorption (legumes, cereals, coffee, tea, sorghum and millet)
- Parasitic infestation such as hookworms, ascaris and schistosomiasis
- Malaria in pregnancy
- Chronic infections such as TB and HIV
- Heavy blood loss prior to or during pregnancy
- High consumption of cow's milk. (it contains high amounts of calcium which inhibit the absorption of iron)
- Pica can result in helminthic infestation, intestinal obstruction and metal poisoning

\section*{Dietary Management of Iron deficiency}

Encourage consumption of foods rich in iron, folic acid, proteins and other nutrients needed for blood production.
- Animal sources - Red meat, Liver, Kidneys, fish, poultry, eggs
- Plant source - legumes (cow peas, kidney beans, Soya beans) fortified cereals, dark green leafy vegetables. Provide foods rich in Vitamin B 12, Folic acid, Vitamin E and C.

NOTE: Iron from plant sources is however not readily bio available as they contain phytates, oxalates and malic acid which inhibit iron absorption. Reduce intake of beverages that contain phenolic compounds and tannin such as tea leaves, wheat and bran.

\section*{Prevention of Iron Deficiency}

The following public health interventions have been shown to increase availability of iron and prevent iron deficiency during pregnancy and in the postpartum period:
- Dietary improvement through consumption of iron-rich foods
- Fortification of foods
- Supplementation of vulnerable groups
- Intestinal worm control
- Malaria and other disease control
- Strengthening health promotion and prevention in school health programs.

\section*{Zinc}

Zinc is the essential trace mineral occurring in the body in larger amounts than any other trace element because it is present in all tissues. Zinc promotes normal growth and development. It is a major component in body enzymes, hormones, genetic material proteins. It promotes wound healing and maintains an effective immune system.

Zinc requirements are highest in the $3^{\text {rd }}$ trimester when the fetus acquires two-thirds of its zinc stores. The RDA for zinc is $15 \mathrm{gm} /$ day for pregnant women, $25 \%$ higher than for non-pregnant women. Inadequate zinc in pregnancy increases the risk of delivering low birth weight infants.

Diets that are very high in calcium, fiber or phytates may decrease zinc absorption. Routine iron and folate supplementation may also impair zinc absorption. Therefore, good dietary sources of zinc as well as dietary habits should be reinforced.

\section*{Food sources:}
- Organs (offal, liver, kidneys), red meat (beef, lamb) white meat (fish and chicken)
- Eggs and dairy products
- Nuts and seeds e.g., pumpkin seeds, water melon seeds, simsim seeds

\section*{Zinc deficiency increases the risk of the following conditions /complications:}
- Pre-eclampsia
- Anemia
- Miscarriage
- Preterm labor and delivery
- Fetal growth restriction
- Premature rupture of the membranes

\section*{lodine}
lodine is essential for the normal functioning of the thyroid gland and for normal mental and physical development. Pregnant women and young children have special needs for iodine. lodine deficiency is the main cause of preventable mental retardation globally. lodine deficiency also causes cretinism, congenital anomalies, stillbirths and abortions.

The recommended dietary allowance (RDA) for a pregnant woman is $175 \mathrm{mg} /$ day and this covers for the extra demands of the fetus. Use of iodized salt is highly recommended.

\section*{Health and economic impact of lodine Deficiency Disorders}
- Increased risk of spontaneous abortions, stillbirths and impaired fetal brain development
- Goiter and cretinism
- Reduced mental capacity and productivity.

\section*{Causes of iodine deficiency:}
- Consumption of diets low in lodine
- Low consumption of iodine fortified foods such as iodized salt
- Anti-nutrient factors such as goitrogens that bind iodine

Food sources: lodized salt, sea/marine fish (shellfish and sardine), lobsters, oysters and crabs, seaweed and plants growing in iodine rich soils.

\section*{Recommended Dietary Allowances (RDA)}

Definition: This refers to the average daily dietary intake levels sufficient to meet the nutrient requirement of $97-98 \%$ of healthy individuals in a particular life stage and gender group.

Estimated Average Requirement (EAR) is the nutrient intake estimated to meet the requirement of half of the healthy individuals in a particular life stage and gender group.

Adequate Intake ( Al ) is the level thought to meet or exceed the requirements of almost all members of a life stage/gender group. An Al is set when there is insufficient data to define an RDA.

Tolerable Upper Intake Level is the highest average daily intake level of a nutrient likely to pose no danger to most individuals in the group.

Tolerable Lower Intake Level is the lowest average daily intake level of a nutrient likely to pose no danger to most individuals in the group

