\section*{Vitamin A}

Vitamin A is an essential nutrient, which is required in small amounts for epithelial cell integrity, effective immune system function and normal sight. Improving Vitamin A status among pregnant women dramatically reduces maternal mortality, fetal growth retardation and is necessary for embryo development and spermatogenesis.

NOTE: Vitamin A supplementation IS NOT recommended in pregnancy as high dose preparations have teratogenic effects.

\section*{Vitamin A Deficiency:}
- Is associated with an increased risk of night blindness, which causes corneal scarring and in severe cases blindness and death
- Increases vulnerability to infections and leads to increased risk of maternal mortality and miscarriage
- Impairs immune system thereby increases risk of infections
- Results in Low Birth Weight and Vitamin A deficient infants
- Is associated with inadequate pregnancy weight gain
- Results in low Vitamin A concentration in Breast Milk

\section*{Food sources:}
- Animal sources (liver, eggs)
- Plant source- Dark green leafy vegetables
- Yellow/orange fruits (Mango, passion, pawpaw)
- Orange-fleshed vegetables (sweet potatoes, pumpkin, carrot and yellow sweet pepper)
- Fortified foods (fats and oils)

\section*{Calcium}

Calcium is needed during pregnancy to promote adequate mineralization of the maternal skeleton \& teeth, for normal blood clotting mechanism, normal muscle action and rapid fetal mineralization of skeletal tissue especially in the 2 nd and 3rd trimester. The RDA for pregnant women is $1200 \mathrm{mg} /$ day $^{10}$. During pregnancy, approximately $25-30 \mathrm{~g}$ of calcium is transferred to the fetus. Most of this is acquired during the third trimester, when calcium is deposited into the fetal skeleton at a rate of about 330 mg per day. To meet the recommended calcium requirements in pregnancy, women should be advised to consume small amounts of milk with snacks and drink fermented milk.

Dietary sources of calcium include:
- Milk, yogurt and cheese
- Sardines ('omena')
- Whole grain cereals
- Green leafy vegetables.
- Food fortified with calcium

\section*{Folic Acid}

The body needs folic acid for the production, repair, and functioning of DNA. Folic acid is particularly important for the rapid cell growth that occurs during pregnancy. Its deficiency is associated with an increased risk of neural tube birth defects. Birth defects are congenital malformation and are structural or functional abnormalities present from birth, they can be caused by a number of factors including micronutrient deficiencies. Spina Bifida is the most common neural birth defect and can be prevented by daily pre conception supplementation with $400 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ of folic acid or a combination with other micronutrients. These birth defects occur early in gestation, before pregnancy is apparent.

\section*{Food sources:}
- Folate is present in a variety of foods such as green leafy vegetables, liver, fruits and brussels.
- The richest sources are spinach, kidney beans, groundnuts, kidney and liver

