\section*{HIGH RISK PREGNANCIES}
- A high-risk pregnancy defined as one which is complicated by factor or factors that adversely affects the pregnancy outcome (maternal, perinatal or both). ${ }^{\underline{20}}$
- Several factors can make a pregnancy high risk, including existing health conditions, the mother's age, lifestyle, and health issues that happen before or during pregnancy.
- High-risk pregnancy can have serious maternal, obstetric, and neonatal complications if left undetected. ${ }^{\underline{22}}$

NB: Pregnancy itself predisposes the client and puts the client at health risk.

\section*{Classification of high-risk pregnancies ${ }^{21}$}
- Pre-existing health conditions: Hypertension, Diabetes mellitus, sexually transmitted diseases, Renal disorders, Thyroid disorders, Autoimmune diseases, Acute surgical problems, genital tract abnormalities, Obesity, Hemoglobinopathies, Severe anemia (Hb $<7 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{dl}$ )
- Age: Young (adolescent pregnancy), Advanced maternal age
- Lifestyle factors: Alcohol abuse, Tobacco smoking, illicit drug use,
- Conditions of pregnancy: Multifetal gestation, Gestational diabetes mellitus, Pre-eclampsia, previous preterm delivery, previous stillbirth, birth defects or genetic conditions in the fetus, placental anomalies, premature rupture of membranes, polyhydramnios, oligohydramnios, prior birth trauma, late spontaneous abortion.

Management and prevention is tailored to the specific pre-existing medical disorder or risk factor. For instance, in a woman suffering from hyperthyroidism, antithyroid drugs would be useful in mitigating against complications that may arise in pregnancy and thus lead to favorable maternal and neonatal outcomes.

Risk assessment in pregnancy helps to predict which women are most likely to experience adverse health events and enables providers to administer risk-appropriate perinatal care. ${ }^{23}$

Effective communication, control and early detection are important tools that doctors must be able to use to plan the best treatment strategies and to minimize the risks of maternal and / or fetal. ${ }^{\underline{26}}$

