\section*{PRETERM PRELABOUR RUPTURE OF MEMBRANES}

\section*{Introduction}

Pre-Labour Rupture of Membranes (PROM) refers to spontaneous rupture of membrane before the onset of uterine contractions. Previously the condition was referred to as premature rupture of membranes.

Preterm Pre-labour Rupture of Membranes (PPROM) refers to spontaneous rupture of membranes occurs beyond 28 weeks but before 37 completed week's gestation and least one hour before the onset of labour

\section*{Epidemiology}

PPROM occurs in about $3 \%$ of pregnancies. It varies considerably between different areas due to different population risk factors. ${ }^{\perp, 2,3}$

Preterm pre-labour rupture of membranes is the primary etiology for $40 \%$ of pre-term births. It is the single most common identifiable factor associated with preterm delivery ${ }^{1,2,3,4,5}$. It precedes about $30-40 \%$ of spontaneous preterm labour. $30-40 \%$ of women with PPROM will deliver within 48 hours and 56 to $63 \%$ within 7 days. ${ }^{2}$

PPROM can lead to significant perinatal morbidity including: Birth asphyxia, Respiratory Distress Syndrome (RDS), neonatal sepsis, umbilical cord prolapse, placental abruption and fetal death. ${ }^{1,} \underline{2}, \underline{3}, \underline{4}$

It has been established that preterm birth is a significant risk factor for long term sequelae such as chronic lung disease, neurosensory impairment, cerebral palsy and developmental delay. ${ }^{4}$

The 3 major causes of death associated with PPROM are: prematurity, neonatal sepsis and pulmonary hypoplasia.

PPROM may be complicated by chorioamnionitis which together with retained products of conception are the major causes of secondary postpartum hemorrhage. ${ }^{\underline{2}}$

