\section*{PRETERM LABOR}

\section*{Definition}

Preterm labour denotes regular uterine contractions accompanied by progressive cervical dilation with or without effacement at less than 37 weeks of gestation. '

Preterm birth occurs between 24- and 37weeks gestation. In two-thirds of cases it occurs following spontaneous onset of labour. Only a minority of women who present with preterm contractions known as threatened premature labour (TPTL) progress to actual labour and delivery ${ }^{2}$

Spontaneous preterm labor, a syndrome caused by multiple pathologic processes, contributes to about $70 \%$ of preterm deliveries. ${ }^{3}$

\section*{Causes of preterm labour ${ }^{\mathbf{1} \boldsymbol{,} \mathbf{4}}$}

\section*{Maternal causes}
- Demographic factors:
- Maternal age $<18$ years and $>35$ years
- Maternal weight $<55 \mathrm{~kg}$
- Uterine distortion due to: mÃ¼llerian duct abnormalities, fibroids
- Cervical incompetence due to: trauma, cone biopsy
- Infection e.g., chorioamnionitis, UTI
- Physical injury
- History of spontaneous preterm birth
- Hormonal imbalances

\section*{Pregnancy/ fetal causes}
- Preterm pre-labour rupture of membranes in current pregnancy
- Antepartum hemorrhage
- Uterine over distension due to multi-fetal gestation or poly-hydramnios
- Fetal anomaly
- Utero-placental insufficiency (e.g., hypertension, insulin-dependent diabetes, drug abuse, smoking>10 cigarettes/day, alcohol consumption)

