\section*{PRETERM BIRTH}

\section*{Definition}
- This is the birth that occurs between 24- and 37-weeks' gestation. In two-thirds of cases it occurs following spontaneous onset of labour. Only a minority of women who present with preterm contractions known as threatened premature labour (TPTL) progress to actual labour and delivery ${ }^{1}$
- Spontaneous preterm labor, a syndrome caused by multiple pathologic processes, contributes to about $70 \%$ of preterm deliveries ${ }^{2}$.
- The risk of preterm deliveries increases with low social-economic status. Countries with the highest rates of preterm deliveries also report that these deliveries occur in persons of lower socioeconomic status ${ }^{3}$.
- Preterm birth is the leading cause of mortality in children under the age of 5 with the incidence increasing in babies of lower gestational ages ${ }^{3}$.

\section*{Epidemiology}
- Yearly, an estimated 15 million babies are born preterm (before 37 completed weeks) with $60 \%$ of this happening in Africa and South Asia. ${ }^{3}$
- The rate of preterm births in countries analyzed in the WHO Global Action report ranged between $5-18 \%$ with Kenya having an estimated range of between $10-15 \% .^{3}$
- A study at the Kenyatta National Referral Hospital in Kenya in 2018 put the prevalence at the institution at $18.3 \% .^{4}$

\section*{Recommendations on preterm births/deliveries ${ }^{5}$}
- Deferring delivery to the 39th week is not recommended if there is a medical or obstetric indication for earlier delivery.
- Recommendations for the timing of delivery for a number of specific conditions (Table I)
- In the case of an anticipated late-preterm delivery a single course of antenatal betamethasone is recommended within 7 days of delivery in select women who have not received a previous course of antenatal corticosteroids.
- However, a medically indicated late-preterm delivery should not be delayed for the administration of antenatal corticosteroids
- The decisions regarding delivery timing are complex and must take into account relative maternal and new-born risks, practice environment, and patient preferences.
- Secondly, late-preterm or early-term deliveries may be required for maternal benefit or new-born benefit, or both.
- In these cases, health care providers will need to weigh competing risks and benefits for the woman and her fetus and the support at the level of health facility adequate or referral mechanisms provided prior to delivery decision.

\section*{Mandatory Responsibility for health Care Providers}
- Prepare the mother and partner for the outcome of the pregnancy
- Prepare resuscitation equipment
- Prepare the environment and alert NBU

