\section*{Glycosylated haemoglobin}

This test reflects the average glucose level in the three months prior to measurement. It is correlated with the risk of congenital malformations, not to any other adverse pregnancy outcomes. It is best used for pregnancy planning and prenatal follow-up in cases of diabetes in pregnancy. HbAIc does not replace the OGTT for the diagnosis of GDM. However, in women with GDM, HbAIc may be used to verify the reliability of their self-monitored glucose reports.

\section*{Self-monitoring of blood glucose}

Self-monitoring of capillary glucose is achieved by multiple daily measurements of capillary blood glucose with a handheld glucometer. It only provides glucose values at the time of measurement and misses in between hyper/hypoglycaemic events.

Self-monitoring of blood glucose is recommended for all pregnant women with diabetes, $3-4$ times a day:
- Fasting: once daily, following at least 8 hours of overnight All fasting
- Postprandial: 2-3 times daily, I or 2 hours after the onset of meals, rotating meals on different days of the wee
