\section*{MALARIA IN PREGNANCY}

\section*{Introduction}

Malaria is a protozoan infection by the Plasmodium species. The plasmodium parasite is transmitted by the female Anopheles mosquito. There are various plasmodium species known to cause malaria with the severity and characteristics of disease varying from species to species.

The plasmodium species known to cause malaria in human beings based on severity of disease in decreasing frequency include:
- Plasmodium falciparum
- Plasmodium vivax
- Plasmodium ovale
- Plasmodium malariae
- Plasmodium knowlesi

Malaria can be classified based on transmission patterns and degrees of transmission as follows: 1,2

\section*{Transmission patterns ${ }^{\mathbf{3}}$}
- Stable malaria (endemic malaria)-A type of malaria transmission that is characterized by a steady prevalence pattern with little variation from one year to the next except as a result of scaling up of malaria interventions or exceptional environmental changes that affect transmission. People living in endemic areas exhibit a high level of immunity (usually acquired) against the malaria parasite. The vulnerable persons in this area are children under 5 years of age and pregnant women.
- Unstable malaria (epidemic malaria) - characterized by large variations in incidence patterns from one year to the next. Epidemics can be attributed to human behavior i.e. migration, environmental and climate factors. People living in areas of unstable malaria exhibit low immunity against the disease.
- Seasonal malaria- Transmission that occurs during some months of the year and is markedly reduced in others particularly when climatic factors do not favor transmission.
- Residual malaria -Persistence of malaria transmission following the implementation of a widely effective malaria program.

\section*{Epidemiology}

Globally, there were 219 million cases of malaria in 2017 and the estimated mortality from malaria related deaths stood at 435,000. The burden was heaviest in the WHO African Region, where an estimated $93 \%$ of all malaria deaths occurred. ${ }^{6}$

Annually, around 125 million pregnancies around the world are at risk from malaria. In subSaharan Africa, an estimated 25 million pregnant women are at risk of infection yearly. $7,8,9$

Malaria in pregnancy is a significant contributing factor to maternal death. It was estimated to have been responsible for approximately $15 \%$ of maternal deaths globally. Annually, Malaria in pregnancy is responsible for $20 \%$ of stillbirths and $11 \%$ of neonatal deaths in sub-Saharan Africa. 10

In Kenya, on an annual basis, approximately I million women who become pregnant are at risk of getting malaria. ${ }^{12}$

