The malaria parasite life cycle involves two hosts (Anopheles mosquito and the human being). In the human being, the lifecycle involves the exo-erythrocytic (liver stage) and the erythrocytic cycles. The Plasmodium vivax and ovale species have the capability to persist in the liver in dormant state which if untreated properly is responsible for relapses and this is a key contributor to malaria in pregnancy in areas where these species are dominant. The erythrocytic cycle (blood stage parasites) are responsible for the clinical manifestations of malaria.

\section*{Pathogenesis ${ }^{\underline{1,14,15}}$}

The median pre-patent period (time from sporozoite inoculation to detectable parasitemia) is 10 days (range $5-10$ days), and the median incubation period (time from sporozoite inoculation to development of symptoms) is 11 days (range 6-14 days) in non-immune individuals.

The incubation period may be significantly prolonged by the level of immunity acquired through previous exposures, use of antimalarial prophylaxis, or by prior partial treatment, which may mitigate, but not prevent the disease

For non-falciparum malaria the incubation period is usually longer (median 15-16 days), and both P . vivax and P . ovale malaria may relapse months or years after exposure due to the presence of hypnozoites in the liver.

Of all the four species, Plasmodium falciparum is known to cause the most severe disease. This lies in its capability to infect red blood cells at any stage of production unlike the other species which have a preference for either young red blood cells or old blood cells.

Also, Plasmodium falciparum causes clumping of infected red blood cells which then stick to endothelial cells lining small blood vessels (sequestration) thus blocking blood flow. Red cell sequestration decreases tissue perfusion and leads to ischemia, which is responsible for the manifestations of cerebral malaria.

Infected red blood cells undergo hemolysis (in circulation and at the spleen). This continuous breakdown of red cells is responsible for anemia which is one of the complications of malaria infection. Hemolysis occurring in the circulation causes a tinge of jaundice due to increased amounts of unconjugated bilirubin which is not water soluble and thus cannot be easily excreted. Sequestration and increased functionality of the spleen causes enlargement; which is a common finding in persons with heavy parasitemia.

In high-transmission settings, where levels of acquired immunity tend to be high, P. falciparum infection is usually asymptomatic in pregnancy. However, parasites may be present in the placenta and lead to maternal anaemia even in the absence of documented peripheral parasitaemia.

In low-transmission settings, where women of reproductive age have relatively little acquired immunity to malaria, malaria in pregnancy is associated with anaemia, an increased risk of severe malaria, and it may lead to spontaneous abortion, stillbirth, prematurity and low birth weight. In such settings, all pregnant women, regardless of the number of times they have been pregnant, are highly vulnerable to malaria.

\section*{Placental Malaria}

Increased susceptibility to malaria infection during pregnancy results in high parasitemia and heavy infiltration of parasite-infected RBCs in placental vasculature, a privilege site where the parasite can evade maternal immune response especially filtration by the spleen. ${ }^{16}$

Malarial infection in the placenta is characterized by sequestration of Plasmodium falciparuminfected erythrocytes and the infiltration of immune cells within the intervillous spaces of the placenta. Deposition of the malarial pigment (hemozoin) turns the placenta black. ${ }^{16}$

Pathologies associated with placental malaria are postulated to be the consequence of a change in immune status from antibody-mediated immune response to cell-mediated immune response.

This increase in cell-mediated immune response is deleterious to the placenta which causes oxidative stress, excess inflammation and apoptotic cell death in the placenta. ${ }^{17}$

Moreover, Heat Shock Proteins that are important for maintenance of normal morphology and physiology of the placenta have been reported in low quantities in malaria-infected placenta.

This causes thickening of the placental basement membrane, perivillous fibrinoid deposits, and syncytial knotting which culminate in an altered exchange system in the feto-maternal circulation.

The resultant placental insufficiency causes intrauterine growth retardation leading to poor pregnancy outcome, such as abortions, stillbirth, intrauterine growth retardation and low birth weight. ${ }^{17}$

