\section*{Algid Malaria ${ }^{15}$}

This is a form of severe malaria although rare notably due to P . falciparum. Individuals with algid malaria have feature indicative of shock (hypotension), metabolic derangements and hypothermia.

Factors involved in algid malaria include:
- Impaired microcirculation due to effect of the malaria parasite on red blood cells
- Production of cytokines which induce inflammatory responses against the parasite whilst at the same time resulting in tissue damage.
- Metabolic derangements due to associated impaired renal dysfunction
- Gastro-intestinal involvement due to obstruction of the mesenteric arteries resulting in ischemia and probable peritonitis.
- Super infection with gram negative bacteria.

\section*{Population risk groups of malaria ${ }^{\mathbf{5}}$}
- Young children in stable transmission areas who have not yet developed protective immunity against the most severe forms of the disease;
- Non-immune pregnant women especially in the first pregnancy
- Semi-immune pregnant women in areas of high transmission in the first pregnancy,
- Semi-immune HIV-infected pregnant women in stable transmission areas, during all pregnancies.
- People with HIV/AIDS;
- International travelers from non-endemic areas because they lack immunity;
- Immigrants from endemic areas and their children living in non-endemic areas and returning to their home countries to visit friends and relatives are similarly at risk because of waning or absent immunity.

