\section*{Diagnostic tests ${ }^{\mathbf{1}, \mathbf{2 1}, \mathbf{2 2}}$}

\section*{Peripheral blood film}

This is a technique employed to detect malaria parasites in circulation. It is the gold standard for laboratory confirmation of malaria. A drop of the patients' blood is placed on a microscope slide and prepared for viewing by use of Giemsa stains. There are two preparations used, they include: Thick film and thin film.

Thick film- Used for detection of malaria parasites but is not used for identification of the species
Thin film- Used for species identification

\section*{Rapid diagnostic test (RDT)}

An alternative method for diagnosis of malaria particularly in areas where good microscopy services cannot be assured.

Malaria RDTs detect specific antigens produced by the plasmodium parasite in the blood of infected individuals. RDTs are lateral flow immune-chromatographic antigen detection tests which rely on the capture of dye-labelled antibodies to produce visible test bands indicating the presence or absence of disease.

The RDTs vary depending on the brand and the impregnated antibodies on the strips. There are some RDTs that only detect one species with others having the capability to detect multiple species. It is recommended that kits with the capability to detect $P$. falciparum be used due to the severity of disease caused by this species.

\section*{Advantages}
- Can be used as point of care test
- Do not require specialized training to perform/interpret the results
- Quick to perform

\section*{Disadvantages}
- Test not confirmatory. Need for microscopy for confirmation of diagnosis
- Lack of data to determine the ability of the test to detect fewer common species

Note: PCR and nucleic acid amplification tests have no role in clinical diagnosis of malaria. However, they can be used for research purposes.

