\section*{Uncomplicated malaria ${ }^{19,21,23,26}$}

\section*{First trimester}

For P falciparum malaria infections during the first trimester, WHO recommends oral quinine hydrochloride $(600 \mathrm{mg}$ every 8 hours $)$ with clindamycin $(10 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ twice a day) for 7 days (or quinine alone if clindamycin is not available)
In situations of failure or unavailability, an artemisinin based combination therapy (ACT) or oral artesunate with clindamycin for 7 days.

Malaria caused by Plasmodium species other than P falciparum (non-falciparum malaria) should be treated with chloroquine; quinine is recommended for chloroquine-resistant infections.

\section*{Second and third trimester}
- Artemether-lumefantrine (AL) currently available as a co-formulated dispersible tablet containing 20 mg of artemether and 120 mg of lumefantrine. This is administered as a 6-dose regimen given over three days (that is 4 tablets stat, repeat after 8 hours, $24 \mathrm{hrs}, 36 \mathrm{hrs}, 48 \mathrm{hrs}$ and 60 hrs ).

Other treatment regimens that can be considered include:
- Dihydroartemisinin-piperaquine
- Artesunate-mefloquine
- Artesunate plus sulfadoxine-pyrimethamine- obsolete in Kenya
- Artesunate-amodiaquine- significant resistance to amodiaquine in Kenya

\section*{Severe malaria in pregnancy}

Intensive care and prompt parenteral antimalarial treatment are crucial to the mother's survival.
The WHO recommends intravenous artesunate as the drug of choice or, if unavailable, intramuscular artemether.

Artesunate-First choice in all trimesters
Dosage IV $2.4 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg} /$ dose given STAT, at 12 h and at 24 h .

Treat for at least 24 h . Once the patient has received at least 24 h of parenteral therapy and can tolerate oral therapy, complete treatment with 3 days of an ACT.

\section*{Quinine}

Loading dose ( 20 mg salt $/ \mathrm{kg}$ ) provides therapeutic plasma concentrations within 4 hours
The maintenance dose of quinine ( $10 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{salt}$ ) is administered at 8 h intervals, starting 8 h after the first dose.

If there is no improvement in the patient's condition within 48 h , the dose should be reduced by one third, i.e. to 10 mg salt/kg every 12 h .

Parenteral quinine has an increased risk of hypoglycemia hence the need for frequent blood glucose monitoring.

