\section*{Management}

Preconception care refers to interventions that identify and modify risks to a couple's health and future pregnancies. It includes prevention and management of health issues that require action before conception. These interventions include:
- Knowledge of HIV status to make informed choices
- Partner involvement
- Good nutrition
- Provision of Comprehensive Post Rape Care services
- STI screening and management
- Contraception to prevent unintended pregnancies
- Life style and behavior change
- Early ART initiation

To reduce MTCT, the woman should conceive when the viral load is undetectable and the CD4 is above 500 cells $/ \mathrm{mm} 3$. She should be advised to ensure that:
- She is in good health, without Opportunistic infections (Ols) or other illnesses due to HIV
- If HIV positive, she should be on optimal therapy with HAART
- She needs to be screened for TB and complete treatment as necessary
- She needs to be on double strength co-trimoxazole $(960 \mathrm{mg})$
- She needs to be treated for any existing STIs and other comorbidities

\section*{Male Partner's Health}

Before the woman tries to get pregnant, the man should be:
- Informed, educated and communicated on PMTCT
- Tested for HIV to rule out discordant couples
- Be in good health and taking and responding to therapy with ARVs for several weeks if HIV-positive and eligible
- Be treated for any existing STIs
- Be circumcised if he is HIV-negative

\section*{Safer Methods to Conceive}
- Encourage condom use during most of the month to prevent transmission of HIV, re-infection with other strains of HIV, or STIs. Consider unprotected sex only when the woman is most fertile. (If cycles are 26-32 days, the fertile period is 8-19th day)
- In case of discordance consider artificial insemination after counselling the couple.

\section*{During Pregnancy and Breastfeeding ${ }^{2}$}

Prevention of mother-to-child transmission of HIV (PMTCT) should be offered as part of a comprehensive package of fully integrated, routine antenatal care interventions. Lifelong ART should be initiated in all pregnant and breastfeeding women living with HIV, regardless of gestational age, WHO clinical stage and at any CD4 count ${ }^{\mathbf{2}}$.

PrEP can complement established prevention strategies for pregnant and breastfeeding women as part of a comprehensive package to reduce HIV transmission.
- ART should be started, ideally, on the same day as HIV diagnosis is made with ongoing enhanced adherence support
- The preferred first line ART regimen for pregnant and breastfeeding women is TDF + 3TC + DTG (WHO JULY 2019) ${ }^{3}$
- Pregnant and breastfeeding women who are virally suppressed on a different first-line regimen should continue their current regimen until complete cessation of breastfeeding, after which they can be considered for regimen optimization
- For pregnant and breastfeeding women newly initiated on ART, obtain VL 3 months after initiation, and then every 6 months until complete cessation of breastfeeding
- For HIV positive women already on ART at the time of confirming pregnancy or breastfeeding, obtain a VL irrespective of when prior VL was done, and then every 6 months until complete cessation of breastfeeding
- For pregnant or breastfeeding women with a detectable VL (any value above LDL): assess for and address potential reasons for viremia, including intensifying adherence support, repeat the VL after 3 months of excellent adherence
- If the repeat VL is $\geq 1,000$ copies $/ \mathrm{ml}$, change to an effective regimen
- If the repeat VL is detectable but $<1,000$ copies $/ \mathrm{ml}$ consult the Regional or National HIV Clinical TWG
- If the repeat VL is undetectable then continue routine monitoring
- All HEI should receive infant ARV prophylaxis consisting of 6 weeks of AZT + NVP and thereafter NVP should be continued until 6 weeks after complete cessation of breastfeeding
- All infants irrespective of HIV status should be exclusively breastfed for the first 6 months of life, with timely introduction of appropriate complementary foods after 6 months, and continued breastfeeding up to 24 months or beyond

\section*{Intrapartum}

\section*{a) Optimal Intrapartum Care}
- Intrapartum care is the management of women from the onset of labour to delivery.
- This period poses the greatest risk for transmission of HIV from the mother to the child (MTCT) with 10 to 20 percent of exposed infants becoming infected at this time in the absence of any intervention.
- In the context of HIV/AIDS, it is, therefore, important to establish the HIV status of women prior to, or during labour and delivery and provide interventions aimed at reducing the risk of transmission.
- With appropriate interventions, the risk of MTCT can be reduced significantly.

The following guidelines should be followed for all women admitted to labour and delivery units
- Minimize vaginal examinations.
- Follow infection prevention and control protocols in conducting delivery.
- Avoid routine artificial rupture of membranes (ARM).
- Avoid routine episiotomy
- Avoid prolonged labour by use of a partograph.
- Avoid unnecessary trauma during delivery.
- Minimize the risk of postpartum haemorrhage
- Assisted vaginal delivery is not a contra-indication in HIV
- Use safe blood transfusion practices.

\section*{b) Specific Management of HIV Positive Pregnant Women}

\section*{Prophylactic Antiretroviral therapies}

The ARV prophylactic regimen depends on whether the mother had ARVs during pregnancy or not. Thus, the health care worker should establish the regimen used during the ANC, whether the woman had taken ARVs at the onset of labour and determine the appropriate intra-partum ARV care as per the national algorithms.

\section*{Mother:}

In Labor and delivery and postnatal period: Combination drug regimens are considered the standard of care for treatment of HIV infection and for prevention of perinatal HIV transmission. Start the mother on lifelong ART and continue with adherence support.

Preferred ART regimen TDF+3TC+DTG (WHO guideline 2019)
Infant: Refer to section 2 on perinatal care of this guideline

\section*{Breastfeeding infant}

All HIV exposed infants (HEI) should receive ARV prophylaxis consisting of 6 weeks of AZT + NVP and thereafter NVP should be continued until 6 weeks after complete cessation of breastfeeding.

All infants including HIV Exposed infants should be exclusively breastfed upto 6 months.

\section*{Mode of delivery}
- Vaginal delivery is appropriate for HIV-infected pregnant women who have been maintained on combined antiretroviral therapy and who have viral loads of 1,000 copies $/ \mathrm{mL}$ or less at or near delivery

The risk of mother-to-child transmission in HIV-infected women with high viral loads can be reduced by performing caesarean deliveries before the onset of labor and before rupture of membranes (termed scheduled caesarean delivery)

\section*{Postpartum care - infant}

All HIV-exposed infants (HEI) should have DNA PCR at 6 weeks and if negative repeat at 6 months and 12 months. An antibody test should be done at 18 months and then repeated every 6 months during breastfeeding. The final antibody test should be performed 6 weeks after complete cessation of breastfeeding.

All infants irrespective of HIV status should be exclusively breastfed for the first 6 months of life, with timely introduction of appropriate complementary foods after 6 months, and continued breastfeeding up to 24 months or beyond.

\section*{Contraception}

Family planning choices amongst PLHIV emphasize on:
- The importance of advocacy for dual contraception especially in HIV positive clients
- Counselling, especially clients with method failure, and those on ARVs or anti TB therapy
- Strengthening linkages with HIV program and ensuring consistent supplies of condoms
