\section*{TB disease (Active TB)}
- TB disease is a state where a person has signs and symptoms of the disease. In this state, there is active multiplication of the bacilli in the body. ${ }^{4}$
- The risk factors for developing disease following infection with the tubercle bacillus include factors that affect body immunity. A significant proportion of cases of TB however does not have any obvious risk factor for disease and unknown biological factors may play a role. ${ }^{1,2,4}$
- Major risk factors: HIV infection, time since infection (Recent infection), poorly treated previous TB ${ }^{4}$
- Other factors: Age (extremes of age), sex (males more than females), malnutrition, diabetes, alcoholism, tobacco smoking, immune suppressing therapy, long term treatment with oral corticosteroids. ${ }^{\underline{4}}$

\section*{Classification of TB disease ${ }^{\underline{2}, \underline{4}}$}

TB occurs in two clinical forms:
- TB in the lungs-- Pulmonary TB (PTB) and
- TB outside the lungs - Extra pulmonary TB (EPTB)

PTB is the most common form of TB accounting for $80 \%$ of the total cases and is of public health concern as it serves as the source of infection.

Extra-pulmonary TB: Extra-pulmonary TB affects other parts of the body outside the lung tissue. Body organs affected by EPTB include: lymph nodes, bones, spine, kidneys, liver, bladder, skin, eyes, and gastro-intestinal system. EPTB can occur in any organ of the body (except nails, hair and teeth)

Pulmonary tuberculosis: This is further classified on the basis of smear microscopy into:
- Smear positive PTB
- Smear Negative PTB

\section*{Smear positive PTB:}

A patient with at least one initial sputum smear examination positive for acid fast bacilli.

\section*{Smear negative PTB}
- At least two sputum specimens at the start of treatment are negative for Acid Fast Bacilli
- Radiologic abnormalities consistent with active pulmonary tuberculosis
- No response to a course of broad-spectrum antibiotics (excluding anti-TB drugs, fluoroquinolones and aminoglycosides especially in HIV negative patients

\section*{Tuberculosis in pregnancy}
- Tuberculosis remains the most common cause of death from infectious agents in childbearingage women (14 to 49 years) worldwide ${ }^{2}$
- Overpopulation, HIV infection, increasing poverty, and the increasing incidence of antibioticresistant isolates are increasing the burden of tuberculosis on women and society. ${ }^{\underline{2}}$
- In the era before chemotherapy, pregnancy and the immediate postpartum period were associated with higher rates of active tuberculosis and faster progression of the disease. ${ }^{\underline{2}}$
- In developing countries, women contribute $40 \%$ to $60 \%$ of household income. Children whose mothers die are 3 to 10 times more likely to die within 2 years than those with both parents alive. This impact is twice that if the father were to die. Tuberculosis kills or maims reproductive-age women, leaving orphans, impoverished families, and limited economic development. ${ }^{1,2,3,4}$
- Pregnancy is a diabetogenic state and diabetes can worsen the clinical course of TB, and TB can worsen glycemic control in people with diabetes. Rates of TB are higher in people with diabetes than in the general population, and diabetes is a common co-morbidity in people with TB. Individuals with both conditions thus require careful clinical management. Strategies are needed to ensure that optimal care is provided to patients with both diseases: TB must be diagnosed early in people with diabetes, and diabetes must be diagnosed early in people with TB.

\section*{KEY CRITICAL POINTS}
- The decision to treat tuberculosis (TB) in pregnancy must consider the potential risks to mother and fetus from medication, and the benefits to mother, foetus and the community. The benefits of treating TB in pregnancy are widely considered to outweigh any risk of treatment.
- Although small concentrations of anti-TB drugs are excreted in breast milk, treatment for TB is generally not considered a contra-indication to breastfeeding, and is not associated with toxicity to the baby.

\section*{Diagnosis of PTB in pregnancy poses unique challenges because: ${ }^{\mathbf{2 ,} \boldsymbol{4}}$}
- The non-specific nature of early pregnancy symptoms (such as frequency of malaise and fatigue) that can mimic early symptoms of TB
- Screening for PTB is not routinely or systematically done in PMTCT programs
- Fear of use of chest radiography in pregnancy due to concerns regarding radiation-induced teratogenicity

\section*{TB in HIV Positive pregnant women ${ }^{3,4}$}
- HIV has led to a rapid increase in the global incidence of TB.
- HIV also increases the likelihood of dying from TB; TB is a leading cause of death among people who are HIV-positive accounting for about $13 \%$ of AIDS deaths worldwide
- HIV and TB form a lethal combination. Someone who is HIV- positive and infected with TB bacilli is many times more likely to develop active tuberculosis.
- TB contributes to the rapid progression of HIV/AIDS
- Both TB and HIV independently increase maternal and perinatal morbidity and mortality
- Risk of Immune Reconstitution Inflammatory Syndrome (IRIS) when ART for PMTCT is given on undiagnosed active TB. This is because ART for PMTCT starts from pregnancy diagnosis for life.

\section*{Effects of TB on pregnancy ${ }^{2,} 3,4$}

Maternal TB has been associated with an increased risk of poor pregnancy outcomes. The outcome is unfavourably influenced by delays in diagnosis or treatment, along with disease other than in lymph nodes.
- Pregnancy does not alter the course of active TB.
- Spontaneous abortion, prematurity, small size for gestational age, neonatal low birth weight, and perinatal deaths ${ }^{3}$
- Women with a late diagnosis of pulmonary TB have an increased risk of obstetric morbidity and a higher risk of miscarriage, eclampsia, and intrapartum complications. ${ }^{3}$

Congenital TB is a rare complication of in utero TB infection due to maternal haematogenous spread. Congenital TB is difficult to diagnose because it is seldom distinguishable from other neonatal or congenital infections. Symptoms usually arise in the second or third week postpartum. Hepatosplenomegaly, respiratory distress and fever are common, and chest radiography is almost universally abnormal ${ }^{7}$

\section*{Clinical features}

\section*{Pulmonary TB presentation ${ }^{2, ~ 3, ~} 4$}
- Tuberculosis should be suspected in any person presenting with a cough of more than two weeks. The cough may be associated with production of blood stained sputum. Other symptoms include: fevers, night sweats, loss of weight, chest pain and shortness of breath.
- All persons presenting with a cough of a duration longer than two weeks should be screened for TB using sputum smear microscopy unless there is another obvious cause of the cough.
- Physical signs may include: Bronchial breath sounds, tachypnea, wasting, hemoptysis

\section*{Differential diagnoses ${ }^{2,} \underline{4}$}

Chronic bronchitis/ COPD, bronchiectasis, lung abscess, lung cancer, heart failure, sarcoidosis, atypical pneumonias e.g. pneumocystis jirovecii pneumonia

\section*{Diagnosis of TB ${ }^{\underline{2,4}}$}

The diagnosis of PTB is based on the following:
- History of presenting complaints (History of prolonged cough is a key symptom)
- Past medical history (Diabetes, HIV)
- History of Contact with TB
- Physical examination
- Sputum AFB microscopy
- Other supportive investigation
- Chest x-ray (Supportive for smear negative TB)
- Specialized bacteriological examination: Culture, molecular tests and drug susceptibility tests for Anti-TB drugs

