Important considerations in sputum examination ${ }^{\underline{2}}$
- An estimated 10,000 organisms $/ \mathrm{ml}$ of sputum are required for acid-fast stain positivity. Identification of a single organism on the entire slide is therefore highly suspicious.
- Paucity of organisms dictates the acquisition of specimens with a high concentration of organisms and thorough examination of the prepared slides.
- At least three early mornings (before rising) specimens are recommended. Early morning gastric aspirates are effective if obtained before ambulation. Thin fluid (i.e. urine) should be examined after sedimentation with centrifugation.
- The use of Gene X-pert in the diagnosis is rapidly changing the specific identification of M. tuberculosis. It can identify as few as 10 organisms in clinical specimens, compared with the 10,000 organisms necessary for AFB smear positivity, possibly within a day.

\section*{Instructing patients to collect sputum specimen ${ }^{4}$}

The following should be observed in the process of collecting and submitting sputum samples to the laboratory for TB diagnosis to ensure production of a quality sputum sample and results:
- Label the sputum containers on the side (NOT ON THE LID) before sputum samples are collected
- Fill in the sputum examination forms ensuring that the patient's contacts are included
- Instruct the patient to collect sputum samples in a well ventilated area preferably outdoors
- The patient should take a deep breath, cough and attempt sputum production. This can be repeated several times
- The patient should close the lid tightly After collecting the sputum
- All collected sputum samples should be submitted to the laboratory as soon as feasible together with a correctly filled sputum examination form

\section*{Sputum induction ${ }^{4}$}
- Inhalation of hypertonic saline (greater $0.9 \%$ ) solution preferably by ultrasonic nebulization
- Bronchial wash or Broncho-alveolar lavage sample obtained through fiber-optic bronchoscopy

Note: These procedures are available only in tertiary institutions in Kenya and because they may lead to a substantial generation of infectious aerosols, should only be carried out in clinical environments with appropriate infection prevention measures in place.

\section*{Sputum culture examination ${ }^{4}$}

Indications for sputum TB culture and DST are:
- Failure of first line treatment (Smears still remains positive at month 5 )
- Lack of smear conversion at end of month 2 while on first line treatment
- Returning after defaulting treatment
- Symptomatic contacts of drug resistant TB cases
- Health care workers
- Relapse

\section*{Chest X-ray ${ }^{\underline{2}, \underline{3}, \underline{4}}$}

The chest x-ray may aid the diagnosis of PTB but it should not be used as the sole means of establishing a TB diagnosis.

All patients with chest x-ray features suggestive of TB should have sputum specimens submitted for microbiological examination. It is a major omission to diagnose TB on the basis of a chest xray ONLY

Radiographic features that usually suggestive PTB include:
- Patchy shadows in lung apices. There may be evidence of cavitation and scarring (fibrosis)
- In HIV infected persons the radiological picture is more often atypical with lower or mid-zone shadows and hilar or mediastinal lymph node enlargement being relatively common.
- Miliary mottling, Pleural and/or pericardial effusion (Cases of Extra Pulmonary Tuberculosis)

Sample from invasive procedures ${ }^{4:}$ TB can be diagnosed through the examination of lung biopsy specimens obtained through:
- Fiber-optic bronchoscopy
- Open lung biopsy or the trans-thoracic route.
- Peritoneal biopsy

Obtaining lung biopsy specimens demands the availability of a technically qualified person and equipment, and therefore these diagnostic techniques are rarely done

Tuberculin skin test: Mantoux test should not be used to diagnose TB in adults. It only indicates that the person has previously been infected with the TB bacillus. Similarly, most serological tests are not able to distinguish latent infection from current active disease and therefore should not be used to diagnose PTB. ${ }^{2,4}$

ESR and other tests ${ }^{4}$ : ESR is usually elevated in active TB, but this test is not sensitive or specific enough to be of value in the diagnosis of PTB

\section*{Screening for TB}
- Reduction of tuberculosis (TB) transmission, morbidity and mortality relies largely on intensified case finding, with consequent early initiation of adequate treatment. This is particularly important among pregnant women in resource-limited settings where TB is a cause of non-obstetrical (indirect) maternal deaths ${ }^{3}$
- Data from Western Cape, South Africa, indicate that there is a 24.2 -fold higher incidence of TB disease among infants born to HIV-infected mothers, diagnosed at a mean age of 6 months, than among those of HIV-negative mothers. This suggests possible under-diagnosis of active tuberculosis during antenatal care ${ }^{3}$
- The World Health Organization recommends ruling out active TB and identifying those in need of further testing among HIV-infected adults using specific symptoms (current cough of any duration, fever, weight loss or night sweats) ${ }^{3}$

