\section*{MATERNAL MENTAL HEALTH}

\section*{Introduction}

Mental health is defined as "a state of well-being in which the individual realizes his or her own abilities, can cope with the normal stresses of life, can work productively and fruitfully, and is able to make a contribution to his or her community." ${ }^{6}$

Maternal mental health aims to address mental health issues in women along a continuum so as to include preconception care, antenatal care, intrapartum care and postpartum care. Previously, maternal mental health issues mostly concentrated on the postpartum period. Major maternal mental health issues are now being referred to in the context of the perinatal period as opposed to the post-partum period.

Pregnancy and the arrival of a new baby signals a time of unparalleled change and hope for the future. For many women, however, it is a challenging time. For a minority of mothers, this period can be overshadowed by mental illness and aggravated by widespread stigma. ${ }^{1}$

Mental illness is treatable and requires the ability to recognize, assess and treat for sustained maternal, new-born and family well-being. The illness may be pre-existent or develop in the course of the mother's life cycle or specific to a given pregnancy. Challenges with continuation, change or cessation of psychotropic drugs exist during pregnancy and lactation.

Perinatal mental illness might also account for a substantial proportion of maternal deaths in lowincome countries if suicide causes were properly classified and reported. ${ }^{1}$

A multi- disciplinary approach is recommended in maternal mental ill health.

\section*{Epidemiology}

Perinatal mental health issues are a common problem globally. In high-income countries, it is estimated that about $10 \%$ of pregnant women and $13 \%$ of women who have just given birth experience some type of mental disorder ${ }^{2}$. In developing countries, the incidence is even higher with an estimate of about $15.6 \%$ mental health problems during pregnancy and $19.8 \%$ mental health problems after child birth ${ }^{3}$.

In Kenya, mental health illness reporting is still not on track and this has resulted in paucity of data relating to mental health problems . ${ }^{4}$

\section*{Maternal mental health recommendations}
- Practice recommendations relate to the screening and assessment of depression symptoms and include the implementation of effective preventive and non-pharmacological treatment interventions, including those focusing on psychosocial and psychological supports.
- Education recommendations include ongoing professional development to enhance nurses and the inter-professional team's knowledge and skills in mental health services and supports for perinatal depression.
- Organization and system policy recommendations have been developed to address the importance of comprehensive and coordinated mental health services and supports for perinatal depression to support care strategies provided by nurses and the inter-professional team ${ }^{5}$.

\section*{Aetiopathogenesis}

The specific causes of maternal mental health illnesses remain unknown. However, fluctuation of maternal hormones has been considered a possible factor but the evidence remains circumstantial.

In the case of peri-partum mood disorders, women might not show gross abnormalities in endocrine physiology, but rather the susceptibility to triggering by childbirth could represent an abnormal response to the normal hormonal fluctuations in the perinatal period. ${ }^{7,8}$

