\section*{Peri-natal anxiety disorders}

Anxiety disorders are the most prevalent psychiatric disorders with women, particularly those in their child bearing years being most affected. Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) is more common in postpartum women relative to the general population. Medical diagnoses such as hypo/hyperthyroidism, anemia, and hypertension have a similar phenotype and should be ruled out ${ }^{8}$.

\section*{Peri-natal depression}

Depression related disorders are common during pregnancy and in the post-partum period. These disorders have a similar phenomenology as non-child bearing depressive disorders. The point prevalence of depression (major and minor) is estimated to be up to $11 \%$ in pregnancy and $13 \%$ in the first 3 months postpartum. A higher prevalence of antenatal and postnatal depression (major and minor) is generally reported in women in low and middle income countries than in women in high income countries ${ }^{11}$.

Perinatal onset of symptoms relating to depression defines symptoms occurring anytime during pregnancy up to I-month post-partum. In addition to depressed mood, loss of interest in pleasurable activities and decreased energy, perinatal depression with a postpartum onset is characterized by obsessive-compulsive, particularly intrusive violent thoughts, psychotic symptoms, and anxiety ${ }^{8,12}$.

For women with suspected post- natal depression, the Edinburgh Postnatal Depression Scale can be used for screening purposes prior to referral to a psychiatrist for further evaluation and management ${ }^{\text {II }}$.

