\section*{Postpartum blues}

Postpartum blues also known as baby blues is the commonest constellation of mood symptoms experienced by women in the immediate postpartum period. This affects approximately $50-80 \%$ of women ${ }^{8}$.

Postpartum blues are transient in nature with an onset after the third postpartum day, typically after the mother has left the hospital post-delivery. Symptoms typically peak by day five and resolve by day ten postpartum ${ }^{8}$.

Postpartum blues commonly affect first-time mothers with no relation to difficult deliveries or obstetric complications.

Symptoms include ${ }^{8}$ :
- Mood lability (rapid mood shifts)
- Tearfulness -not related to depressive episodes
- Irritability
- Anxiety
- Insomnia
- Lack of energy and increased fatigue
- Loss of appetite
- A general experience of feeling overwhelmed-particularly with regard to newborn caregiving tasks

\section*{Management ${ }^{8}$}

No need for pharmacological treatment.
Psychosocial treatment modalities apply and can include:
- Psychoeducation- Should begin in the antenatal period where the mother is informed on the psychological aspects of pregnancy, childbirth and the postpartum period. Also, the mother can join a support group of new mothers or talk to other mothers.
- Encourage the mother to seek for help from the spouse, family members and friends so as to ease the burden of child care
- Careful monitoring for a worsening or prolongation of symptoms.

