\section*{Relative Contraindications to Amniotomy}
- Infections i.e., Hepatitis B, Hepatitis C, HSV and HIV in order to minimise the hazards to the foetus of ascending infection.
- Presenting part high and mobile
- Active management of labour
- Intrapartum foetal surveillance

At admission intermittent auscultation and during labour CTG can be used

\section*{Position and ambulation}

Women should be encouraged to ambulate freely according to comfort, where it does not compromise maternal and fetal observations in labour

\section*{Provision of analgesia}
- The facility needs to inform the parturient the types of analgesia available and noting their limitations refer accordingly
- Pharmacological and non- pharmacological methods need to be offered and provided
- Each labour unit should have a guideline for opioid use during labour that includes the mechanisms of action, average and maximum doses, route of administration, possible maternal and fetal side effects, precautions, and opioid antagonists and resuscitative measures for each drug.
- Epidural analgesia provides the most effective pain relief for women in labour. The timing of initiation of labour epidural is dependent on the woman's choice once the diagnosis of labour has been established.

\section*{Fluids and oral intake}
- Women should be encouraged to only have clear fluids and light diet in the active phase of labour to minimise the small risk of aspiration pneumonitis.
- Routine intravenous fluids are not recommended in labour and increases unnecessary costs. 9
- Dehydration may increase the length of labour necessitating augmentation of labour
- Intravenous fluid replacement may be necessary in women unable to tolerate sufficient oral intake, and is recommended for volume loading prior to epidural anaesthesia.
- Oral medications can be given as usual in labour, although absorption may be impaired in established labour and another route may need to be considered (e.g. for anticonvulsants).

\section*{Antibiotics}
- Indications for antibiotic administration in labour:
- For prevention of early onset Group B Streptococcus (GBS) infection
- For women at risk of chorioamnionitis or where other bacterial infection is suspected - E.g. fever > 38 on one occasion or > 37.5 on two occasions
- For women with cardiac lesions susceptible to infective endocarditis.

\section*{Antispasmodics in labour}

The use of antispasmodic agents for prevention of delay in labour is not recommended. ${ }^{10}$

\section*{Perineall pubic shaving at birth}

Routine perineal/pubic shaving prior to giving vaginal birth is not recommended. ${ }^{11}$

