\section*{Fundal pressure at birth}

Application of manual fundal pressure to facilitate childbirth during the second stage of labour is not recommended. ${ }^{26}$

\section*{Episiotomy}

This is no benefit from routine episiotomy. Indications where it may be considered is with a high likelihood of severe laceration;
- Soft tissue dystocia;
- A requirement to accelerate the birth of a compromised foetus;
- The need to facilitate operative vaginal birth;
- A history of Female Genital Mutilation (FGM).
- Third stage of labour

There is no room for expectant (physiological) management of third stage due to the risk of immediate postpartum haemorrhage, increased risk for blood transfusion and a flaccid uterus that can undergo acute uterine inversion.

\section*{Recommendation}

Active management of third stage of labour (AMSTL) includes
- Administration of uterotonics e.g. I..M 10 I.U oxytocin within one minute of delivery after ruling out absence of $2^{\text {nd }}$ twin
- Delivery of placenta by Controlled Cord Traction (C.T.T recommended for all women)
- Uterine massage

This is followed by assisted delivery of the placenta and membranes by controlled cord traction (CCT) and is recommended for all women.

\section*{Other drugs that can be used in AMTSL:}
- Oxytocin 5 or 10 units (intramuscularly or intravenously)
- Heat stable Carbetocin 100ug (intramuscularly or intravenously)
- Syntometrine intramuscularly l ml stat
- Ergometrine IM 0.2 mg stat
- Ergometrine and oxytocin (ergometrine $0.2 \mathrm{mg}+$ oxytocin 5 units)
- Misoprostol oral, sublingual, or per rectal 200 ug stat

N/B: Ergometrine contraindicated in hypertensive patients and cardiac patients and should not be injected into blood vessels

\section*{Delayed Cord clamping}
- There should be no urgency to cut the umbilical cord and this can be done between I-3 minutes.
- In preterm infants, delayed cord clamping is associated with a reduced risk of requiring transfusion, infection, necrotising enterocolitis and intraventricular haemorrhage.
- In term infants delayed cord clamping is associated with an increased haematocrit and reduced iron deficiency at $3-6$ months of age. This is more so amongst mothers where iron stores are low, or in infants who will be exclusively breastfed without iron supplementation.
- Approximately $75 \%$ of available placental blood for transfusion is achieved in the first minute after birth, and the transfer of blood from placenta to new-born is facilitated by the infant being held below the level of the in-situ placenta.
- If the infant is held between 10 cm above to 10 cm below the level of the placenta, transfusion is complete within 3 minutes.
- If the infant is held 40 cm below the placenta, transfusion time is shortened to 1 minute.
- Application of chlorhexidine digluconate $7.1 \%$ on the cord

\section*{Management of $4{ }^{\text {th }}$ Stage of Labour}
- The fourth stage of labour is the first hour after delivery of the placenta. The mother should remain in the labour ward where her condition should be assessed, the perineum, vagina, and cervix should be examined for tears.
- During this time, observe the mother every 15 minutes for vital signs and vaginal bleeding. Monitor the new-born's condition for bleeding from the cord, maintenance of body temperature and where appropriate, encourage initiation of breastfeeding within the first hour of birth
- Continuity of care for positive childbirth experience (context specific recommendation)
- Midwife-led continuity-of-care models, in which a known midwife or small group of known midwives supports a woman throughout the antenatal, intrapartum and postnatal continuum, are recommended for pregnant women in settings with well-functioning midwifery programmes. ${ }^{28}$

\section*{Immediate new-born care}
1. Initial assessment upon delivery
2. Skin to skin contact if no maternal and neonatal complications
3. Apgar scores should be completed at I and 5 minutes of age.
4. Secondary neonatal assessment in the early postpartum period
5. Intramuscular vitamin K administration is recommended, and in some centres, Hepatitis B vaccination

\section*{Routine (targeted) postpartum care}

Maternal assessment in fourth stage ( 6 hours)
- Routine MEOW Chart monitoring
- Initiation of breastfeeding health initiative
- Immediate postpartum family planning
- Maternal danger signs
- Clinical assessment
- Multimodal management of pain with analgesics an early ambulation
- Surgical site infection prevention and prophylaxis for DVT
- Access to emergency care with complications

\section*{Documentation and Debrief}
1. Patients and family expectations and experience are expressed
2. Provides an opportunity to explain an adverse outcome
3. Staff given opportunity to debrief with adverse outcome (Near miss and MPDSR)
4. Promotes learning, linkage and health system change
5. Identifies vulnerable team members that need support after an adverse outcome
6. Risk mitigation for medico legal issues

