\section*{PEOPLE LIVING WITH DISABILITY}

\section*{Introduction}

People Living with Disability (PLWD) have less access to health care and health promotion services. According to WHO- World Bank, 2011 as cited by Unicef ', Women with disabilities are recognized as particularly disadvantaged, experiencing exclusion double burden to their gender and disability condition and often very vulnerable to abuse.

Throughout the developing world, it is reported that people with disabilities have less access to healthcare services due to barriers and often experience unmet healthcare needs. Women with disabilities face more challenges in accessing healthcare, particularly maternal healthcare-resulting in higher risk situations and poorer outcomes than women without disabilities ${ }^{2,4}$.

\section*{Definition}

Disability is defined as a long-term physical, mental, intellectual or sensory impairment which in interaction with various barriers may hinder a person's full and effective participation in society on an equal basis with others.

Women with disabilities are particularly vulnerable to deficiencies in healthcare services depending on disability type and setting. Some health conditions associated with disability result in poorer health and extensive healthcare needs, others do not. However, all people with disabilities also have the same general healthcare needs as everyone else, and therefore need access to mainstream healthcare services

Most women with disability are able to become pregnant and to have normal labour experience some women with disability have experiences that review some thoughts to advanced planning.

\section*{Epidemiology}

According to WHO and the World Bank, over a billion people, about $15 \%$ of the world's population and $16 \%$ of the world's women, have some form of disability, $80 \%$ of them live in limitedresource settings'. By 2009, 1.7 million persons were living with disability in Kenya. According to the KNBS report 2013, $3.5 \%$ women constitute persons living with disability in Kenya.

There are various types of disabilities ranging from physiological, functional to motor impairments.
Some of the common disabilities include:
- Visual impairment
- Auditory impairments
- Intellectual disabilities
- Speech and language disorders
- Physical disabilities

\section*{Recommendations ${ }^{\text {I, } 4}$}

Special programmes are needed to meet the special needs of women with disabilities. These should include:
- Training service providers on providing services to the women with disabilities e.g. in communication skills with sensory disabled and to provide individualized care on types of disability
- Disseminating guidelines for staff on how to deal with persons with disabilities during pregnancy, labour childbirth and in the postnatal period
- Ensure that the existing and proposed physical infrastructure is universally accessible and friendly to PWDs in all aspects to include pregnancy, labour and childbirth and postnatal care
- Integrate reproductive health and HIV/AIDS information and services for PLWD accessing pregnancy, delivery, and postnatal services.
- Designing services that can provide properly packaged information for PWDs.
- Make MCH programmes more inclusive by investing in outreach and family-based approaches:
- Disseminating accessibility standards and guidelines to promote removing the most noticeable architectural barriers in MCH clinics
- Implementing advocacy programmes with the communities to ensure that pregnant women with disabilities demand and use services in both rural and urban areas.
- Finding solutions to the transportation needs of pregnant women with disabilities, e.g. providing vouchers.
- Disability counsellors can provide support for pregnant women living with disabilities and other effective services in the community and the clinics as well. This would contribute to strengthening PHC programmes, which is one of the proposed platforms for meeting Universal Health Coverage

