In making interpretations of CTG tracings there is need to have clear understanding of the pathophysiology of the fetus oxygenation; relate this to intrapartum uterine contractions, underlying maternal / fetal medical and obstetric conditions, have competent staff for decision making and institution of appropriate and timely management with access to a robust and supportive health system to expedite delivery when complications occur.

Continuous monitoring is advocated for high-risk cases for fetal hypoxia/acidosis, whether due to maternal health conditions (such as vaginal haemorrhage and maternal pyrexia), abnormal fetal growth during pregnancy, epidural analgesia, meconium stained liquor, or the possibility of excessive uterine activity, as occurs with induced or augmented labor. Continuous CTG is also recommended when abnormalities are detected during intermittent fetal auscultation.

The use of continuous intrapartum CTG in low-risk women is more controversial, although it has become standard of care in many countries. An alternative approach is to provide intermittent CTG monitoring alternating with fetal heart rate (FHR) auscultation. There is some evidence to support that this is associated with similar neonatal outcomes in low-risk pregnancies.

\section*{Clinical screening of Non reassuring fetal status (NRFS)}

NRFS can be identified in any of the following ways: -
- Fetal heart rate that uses intermittent use of the fetoscope assessed before, during and after a uterine contraction.
- Presence of meconium stained liquor and grade either following spontaneous rupture of membranes or artificial rupture of membranes
- Non-stress testing done when monitoring the fetal heart rate during evaluation of the biophysical profile and doppler studies velocity- middle cerebral artery, umbilical artery (ultrasound)
- Fetal movement by maternal perception
- Fetal pulse oximetry, scalp blood pH assessment
- Fetal surveillance intrapartum: The relation of the passage and power to the passenger during the events of labour (monitored with use of the partograph)
- Fetal Stress testing associated with spontaneous labour or induction of labor or augmentation of labor
- By use of the CTG

\section*{Maternal position for CTG tracing}

The lateral recumbent, half-sitting, and upright positions are preferable alternatives for CTG tracing as the maternal supine position associated with aorto-caval compression by the pregnant uterus, affecting placental perfusion and fetal oxygenation and should be avoided for prolonged duration.

Paper scales have 1 to $3 \mathrm{~cm} / \mathrm{min}$ is recommended ( $1 \mathrm{~cm} / \mathrm{min}$ favorable) but differ with countries. The vertical scale used for registration and viewing may also be different, and available alternatives are 20 or $30 \mathrm{bpm} / \mathrm{cm}$. Important that the clinician familiarizes appropriately with the tracing to make sound judgement

\section*{External versus internal fetal heart monitoring}

External FHR monitoring uses a Doppler ultrasound transducer. External FHR monitoring is more prone to signal loss, to inadvertent monitoring of the maternal heart rate, and to signal artefacts such as double-counting and half-counting, particularly during the second stage of labor. It may also not record fetal cardiac arrhythmias accurately.

Internal FHR monitoring using a fetal electrode. It evaluates the time intervals between successive heart beats by identifying $R$ waves on the fetal electrocardiogram QRS complex, and therefore measures ventricular depolarization cycles. This method provides a more accurate evaluation of intervals between cardiac cycles, but it is more expensive because it requires a disposable electrode.

It requires ruptured membranes and has established contraindications, mainly related to the increased risk of vertical transmission of infections. It should not be used in patients with active genital herpes infection, those who are seropositive to hepatitis B, C, D, E, or to HIV. Fetal electrode placement should also preferably be avoided in very preterm foetuses (under 32 weeks of gestation).

Recommendation: External FHR monitoring is the recommended initial method for routine intrapartum monitoring. If an atypical tracing obtained, then internal fetal heart monitoring can be employed as long as there is no contraindication.

\section*{External versus internal uterine contraction monitoring}

External monitoring of uterine contractions using a tocodynamometer evaluates increased myometrial tension measured through the abdominal wall. This technology only provides accurate information on the frequency of contractions. It is not possible to extract reliable information regarding the intensity and duration of contractions, nor on basal uterine tone.

Internal monitoring of uterine contractions using an intrauterine catheter provides quantitative information on the intensity and duration of contractions, as well as on basal uterine tone, but it is more expensive as the catheter is disposable, and requires ruptured membranes. Contraindications include uterine haemorrhage of unknown cause and placenta Previa. It may
also be associated with a small risk of fetal injury, placental haemorrhage, uterine perforation, and infection. The routine use of intrauterine pressure catheters has not been shown to be associated with improved outcomes in induced and augmented labour, and so it is not recommended for routine clinical use.

\section*{Simultaneous monitoring of maternal heart rate}

CTG monitors provide the possibility of continuous MHR monitoring, either by electrocardiography or pulse oximetry. This is important with fetal heart block and in second stage of labor when accelerations coincide with contractions and expulsive efforts or there is maternal fever.

