\section*{Definition}

Augmentation of labour is the process of stimulating the uterus to increase the frequency, duration and intensity of contractions after the onset of spontaneous labour

\section*{Causes}

Common underlying causes include inefficient uterine contractions, abnormal fetal presentation or position, inadequate bony pelvis or soft tissue abnormalities of the mother.

\section*{Indications}
- Augmentation of labour has commonly been used to treat delayed labour when uterine contractions are assessed to be insufficiently strong or inappropriately coordinated to dilate the Cervix
- Augmentation of labour should be performed only when there is a clear medical indication and the expected benefits outweigh the potential harms.
- Retained second twin

\section*{Contraindications}
- Cephalopelvic disproportion. (This principle is relevant for all women but is even more crucial for multiparous women).
- Previous uterine rupture
- Previous Cesarean scar
- Non reassuring fetal status in early labour
- Meconium-stained liquor

\section*{Management}

\section*{Diagnosis}

Can be made by proper history taking and physical examination and monitoring of labour by proper use of partograph

\section*{Treatment/ Augmentation process}

The traditional methods of labour augmentation have been with the use of intravenous oxytocin infusion and artificial rupture of the membranes (amniotomy)

Oxytocin augmentation is recommended in women with ineffective contractions. Oxytocin Augmentation shortens birth outcomes but eventual reduction in instrumental delivery is not documented

\section*{Administration of oxytocin}

IV 5 IU in 500 mls of $\mathrm{N} /$ saline starting at 10 drops $/ \mathrm{min}$ (Primigravida) and titrating by 10 drops $/ \mathrm{min}$ up to a max of $60 \mathrm{drops} / \mathrm{min}$. For Multiparous, start at IV 2.5 IU at $10 \mathrm{drops} / \mathrm{min}$ up to the max of 60drops /min

The fetus should be monitored continuously with CTG when the labour is accelerated with oxytocin

Duration, Strength and frequency of contractions should be continuously recorded on the partograph

\section*{Guiding principles}

The principles are not by themselves specific recommendations but are expected to guide endusers in the process of adapting and implementing the guideline in a range of contexts and settings.
- Application of the recommendations should be based on consideration of the general condition of the woman and her baby, her wishes and preferences, and respect for her dignity and autonomy
- Women undergoing augmentation of labour, particularly with oxytocin, should not be left unattended.
- As the evidence for these recommendations was largely informed by studies conducted among women with pregnancies in cephalic presentation and unscarred uterus, they should not be applied to women with abnormal fetal presentation (including breech) or scarred uterus.
- Augmentation of labour should be performed with caution as the procedure carries the risk of uterine hyperstimulation, with the potential consequences of fetal distress and uterine rupture.
- Wherever augmentation of labour is performed, facilities should be available to closely and regularly monitor fetal heart rate and uterine contraction pattern.
- Augmentation of labour should be carried out in facilities where there is capacity to manage its potential outcomes, including adverse effects and failure to achieve vaginal birth.

