\section*{Contraindications to Induction of Labour by Cervical Ripening}

Any contraindication for vaginal birth including but not limited to:
- Placenta Previa- type 2B,3\&4, vasa Previa, or a cord presentation
- Abnormal foetal lie or presentation (e.g., a transverse lie or footling breech)
- Prior classical Caesarean section or inverted "T" uterine incision
- Significant previous uterine surgery (i.e., full thickness myometrial incision)
- Active genital herpes simplex virus
- Pelvic structural deformities
- Invasive cervical carcinoma
- Previous uterine rupture
- Estimated weeks of gestation of less than 35 weeks
- Known hypersensitivity to dinoprostone or its constituents
- Abnormal foetal heart rate
- Regular contractions

\section*{Pain relief}
- Women should be informed of the availability of pain relief options.
- Women should be provided pain relief appropriate for them after counselling. This can range from simple analgesics to epidural analgesia.
- Women should be encouraged to use breathing and relaxation techniques in labour.
- There is no need to wait for labour analgesia arbitrarily till the cervical dilation has reached $4-5 \mathrm{~cm} .^{8,9}$
- If given early in labour; it does not affect the progress of labour.
- Pethidine and opioid analgesia can be used for short term pain relief, preferably in early labour ${ }^{10}$

