\section*{Robson Classification ${ }^{\underline{9}}$}

This system was proposed by WHO in 2015 in order to provide a classification system to monitor and compare CS rates at facility level in a standardized, reliable, consistent and action-oriented manner.

This was arrived at after it was noted that monitoring of CS rates between different settings over periods of time was difficult to interpret and compare due to: differences in hospital factors and infrastructure, differences in the characteristics of the obstetric population served and differences in clinical management protocols.

WHO expects that this classification will help healthcare facilities to:
- Identify and analyze the groups of women which contribute most and least to overall caesarean section rates
- Compare practice in these groups of women with other units who have more desirable results and consider changes in practice
- Assess the effectiveness of strategies or interventions targeted at optimizing the use of caesarean section
- Assess the quality of care and of clinical management practices by analyzing outcomes by groups of women
- Assess the quality of the data collected and raise staff awareness about the importance of this data, its interpretation and use.

The Robson system classifies all women admitted for delivery (not women who've only had a caesarean section) into one of 10 groups based on: number of previous pregnancies, previous uterine scars, current gestation type (singleton vs multiple gestation), gestational age, presentation and lie of the baby (cephalic, breech, transverse) and onset of labor.

