\section*{Peri-mortem Caesarean Delivery}
- A perimortem caesarean delivery is defined as a caesarean section performed during imminent cardiac arrest or active cardiac arrest, with the ultimate goal to successfully resuscitate the mother and improve fetal survivability. It is also referred to as resuscitative hysterotomy. ${ }^{\underline{11}}$
- The possible etiology of cardiac arrest in pregnancy includes: anesthetic complications, haemorrhage, cardiovascular diseases, drugs, emboli, fever and hypertension. ${ }^{\underline{14}}$
- Physiological changes in pregnancy and the effects of the gravid uterus, have been shown to have an effect on maternal systemic circulation. This has made perimortem caesarean delivery an option in instances where the maternal status does not improve albeit adequate resuscitation. ${ }^{\underline{14}}$
- During resuscitation, it has been noted that with the term gravid woman lying on her back, chest compressions were ineffective due to aortocaval obstruction. Paradoxically, after perimortem delivery, it has been found that resuscitation attempts are more feasible with increased rates of maternal revival. $\underline{11}, \underline{12}, \underline{14}$
- A perimortem caesarean delivery or rather the decision to conduct a perimortem caesarean delivery should be made within the first four minutes of failed resuscitation to avoid end organ damage secondary to hypoperfusion thereby ensuring possible maternal and neonatal survival. However, studies have shown chances of neonatal survival even after 15 minutes of failed resuscitation attempts. ${ }^{\underline{11}, \underline{12}, \underline{14}}$

