\section*{Caesarean hysterectomy}
- Caesarean hysterectomy refers to the removal of the uterus after conducting a caesarean delivery. Caesarean hysterectomy can be classified into three categories: Emergent, Indicative non-emergent and Elective cases. ${ }^{15}$
- Emergent cases: This describes a scenario in which a caesarean section has been carried out, then certain complications emerge intraoperatively that necessitate a hysterectomy. These complications include: adherent placenta and post-partum haemorrhage that does not respond to initial treatment modalities. ${ }^{15}$
- Indicative non-emergent cases: This describes a case where, a woman is known to have a certain condition and a hysterectomy is indicated as the best treatment modality after delivery of the fetus. These include: Cervical cancer, uterine fibroids and adnexal disease. ${ }^{15}$
- Elective cases: these are instances in which a woman makes the conscious decision to have the uterus removed after delivery. This is mostly done as a form of permanent contraception (Sterilization). ${ }^{15}$

\section*{Surgical technique ${ }^{15}$}

A caesarean hysterectomy encompasses two separate procedures in one:
- Caesarean section delivery
- Hysterectomy
- The fetus is delivered through the same recommended caesarean section technique with removal of the placenta (if feasible).
- In instances where an adherent placenta was suspected preoperatively, then it is recommended that the incisions made are away from the placenta to avoid excessive bleeding.
- The uterus is then brought out through the abdominal incision.
- The hysterectomy technique is similar to that performed in a routine hysterectomy. However, physiologic changes in the maternal pelvis that accompany pregnancy result in various challenges during the procedure. Therefore, the increased vasculature of the uterus (size and tortuosity) is of concern.
- Clamping and division of the round ligaments
- Opening of the uterovesical fold (using monopolar diathermy) and reflection of the bladder from the lower uterine segment
- Lateral incision of the broad ligament (this is done parallel to the infundibulo-pelvic ligament)
- Dissection of the loose areolar tissue encountered to enable visualization of the retroperitoneal space and the ureter throughout its course. Note that the loose areolar tissue is more pronounced due to pregnancy.
- Clamping and ligation of the tubal and ovarian ligament.
- Free dissection and displacement of the bladder below the operative field. The challenges encountered may be presence of adhesive bands which may necessitate sharp dissection.
- Clamping of the uterine vessels so as to diminish the uterine blood supply. Most surgeries are done with an aim to conserve the ovaries (unless infundibulo-pelvic ligament hematomas occur). This is done by placing the clamps close to the uterus.
- Based on the hemostatic stability of the patient/or reason that necessitated the caesarean hysterectomy, the surgeon decides between performing a total or subtotal hysterectomy. The subtotal hysterectomy is preferred in unstable patients since the operative time is substantially shortened.
- Amputation of the uterus and approximation of the cervical stump in an anterior-to-posterior fashion using interrupted figure-of-eight ligatures.
- Further dissection is done with an aim to identify the junction between the cervix and the vagina. The cervix is then amputated and the vaginal vault is then secured.
- If bladder injury is suspected, then the integrity of the bladder is tested through use of opaque solutions with the surgical field inspected for any spills. If injury is confirmed, then repair should be done and integrity confirmed again before closure. Postoperative antibiotic coverage and Foley catheter drainage of the bladder should then be continued for 7-10 days.

