\section*{Risk Factors}

Procedures are mostly carried out on young girls sometime between infancy and adolescence, and occasionally on adult women. Globally, more than 3 million girls are estimated to be at risk for FGM annually (UNICEF 2013).
- Where FGM is a social convention (social norm), the social pressure to conform to what others do and have been doing, as well as the need to be accepted socially and the fear of being rejected by the community, are strong motivations to perpetuate the practice. In some communities, FGM is almost universally performed and unquestioned.
- FGM is often considered a necessary part of raising a girl, and a way to prepare her for adulthood and marriage.
- FGM is often motivated by beliefs about what is considered acceptable sexual behavior. It aims to ensure premarital virginity and marital fidelity. FGM is in many communities believed to reduce a woman's libido and therefore believed to help her resist extramarital sexual acts. When a vaginal opening is covered or narrowed (type 3), the fear of the pain of opening it, and the fear that this will be found out, is expected to further discourage extramarital sexual intercourse among women with this type of FGM.
- Where it is believed that being cut increases marriageability, FGM is more likely to be carried out.
- FGM is associated with cultural ideals of femininity and modesty, which include the notion that girls are clean and beautiful after removal of body parts that are considered unclean, unfeminine or male.
- Though no religious scripts prescribe the practice, practitioners often believe the practice has religious support.
- Religious leaders take varying positions with regard to FGM: some promote it, some consider it irrelevant to religion, and others contribute to its elimination.
- Local structures of power and authority, such as community leaders, religious leaders, circumcisers, and even some medical personnel can contribute to upholding the practice.
- In most societies, where FGM is practiced, it is considered a cultural tradition, which is often used as an argument for its continuation.
- In some societies, recent adoption of the practice is linked to copying the traditions of neighboring groups. Sometimes it has started as part of a wider religious or traditional revival movement.

\section*{Prevention}
- Change traditions with support of older generation
- Educate girls on the rights to decide what happens to their body
- Speak out (Advocacy) on the reality and risk of FGM
- Spread understanding that religion does not demand FGM
- Tackle the secrecy that allows cutting to continue
- Keep pushing for FGM to be banned- The family, community and government to support ending FGM by enforcing FGM law Act 2011
- Enforce laws on eradication of Medicalisation of FGM

\section*{Outcome of FGM}

\section*{Immediate complications can include:}
- Severe pain
- Excessive bleeding (hemorrhage)
- Genital tissue swelling
- Fever
- Infections e.g., tetanus
- Urinary problems
- Wound healing problems
- Injury to surrounding genital tissue
- Shock
- Death

\section*{Long-term consequences can include:}
- Urinary problems (painful urination, urinary tract infections);
- Vaginal problems (discharge, itching, bacterial vaginosis and other infections);
- Menstrual problems (painful menstruations, difficulty in passing menstrual blood, etc.);
- Scar tissue and keloid;
- Impaired sexual function (pain during intercourse, decreased satisfaction, etc.);
- Increased risk of childbirth complications (difficult delivery, excessive bleeding, caesarean section, need to resuscitate the baby, etc.) And new-born deaths;
- Need for later surgeries: for example, the FGM procedure that seals or narrows a vaginal opening (type 3) needs to be cut open later to allow for sexual intercourse and childbirth (deinfibulation). Sometimes genital tissue is stitched again several times, including after childbirth, hence the woman goes through repeated opening and closing procedures, further increasing both immediate and long-term risks;
- Psychological problems (depression, anxiety, post-traumatic stress disorder, low self-esteem, etc.);

\section*{Management of childbirth in a woman with FGM}

\section*{Diagnosis}
- Detailed history taking
- Physical examination -inspection of external genitalia and classification of the type of FGM

\section*{Antenatal booking visits:}
- Ask all women about FGM
- Women who have undergone Type I, II and III FGM must be examined at their first antenatal attendance to assess the degree of damage.
- Type I, II, and III FGM can produce severe vulval and vaginal scarring, which may cause obstruction during assessment and delivery
- Record the appearance of the vulva on the clients ANC card -Can help avoid unnecessary future examination

\section*{Management during labor}
- IF FGM has caused a tight introitus there is a need to increase the vaginal opening by performing an episiotomy
- Women with type I, tend to be able to deliver vaginally without episiotomy unless there is extensive scarring causing inelasticity of the perineum
- Women with type III: must be opened up during the second stage of labor when the presenting part is pressing on the vulva
- EPISIOTOMY usually performed during the second stage of labor however can be performed earlier
- If a woman presents with type III C/S is more appropriate than deinfibulation and vaginal delivery;
- Explain the need for operation and seek her consent to perform it
- Or refer her to a CEMONC

\section*{Postpartum management}
- Check for retained products make sure uterus is well contracted
- Check the bladder -empty if necessary, or administer uterotonics drugs
- Check for tears on the vulva and inside the birth canal
- if there is bleeding or tears take appropriate action immediately
- provide counselling to woman about outcome /complications/future management

Remember women with FGM are at risk of:
- PPH
- Urinary retention
- Secondary bleeding due to retained products
- Infection
- Tissue injury
- VVF
- Neonatal asphyxia

