\section*{Introduction}

It accounts for $3.5 \%$ of term singleton deliveries and about $25 \%$ of cases before 30 weeks of gestation as most cases undergo spontaneous cephalic version up to term. It is more common in preterm deliveries. It is associated with uterine and congenital abnormalities, has a significant recurrence risk and is more common in nulliparous women. Term babies presenting by the breech have worse outcomes than cephalic ones, irrespective of the mode of delivery. Breech delivery carries a perinatal mortality risk of 2.0 per 1000 compared to a perinatal mortality risk of 0.5 per 1000 for caesarean section and 1.0 per 1000 cephalic vaginal birth.

In breech presentation, labour and birth carry increased risk of morbidity and mortality compared to cephalic presentation. Caesarean delivery is often recommended as a safer method of birth for breech presentation, but carries risk for the mother both immediately and in future pregnancies.

While vaginal birth could be safely completed, patients need to be carefully selected for their suitability, thoroughly counselled and delivered in appropriate facilities where skilled personnel are available.

External Cephalic Version (ECV), a procedure to turn the foetus from a breech to a cephalic presentation, can reduce the incidence of breech presentation in labour and should be offered to some mothers late in the pregnancy.

