\section*{TRANSVERSE LIE}

\section*{Introduction}

A transverse lie constitutes an absolute foeto-pelvic disproportion, and vaginal delivery is impossible. This is an obstetric emergency, because labour is obstructed and there is a risk of uterine rupture and foetal distress.

\section*{Definition}

Transverse lie refers to a foetal presentation in which the foetal longitudinal axis lies perpendicular to the long axis of the uterus. It can occur in either of two configurations:
- The curvature of the foetal spine is oriented upward (also called "back up" or dorsosuperior), and the foetal small parts and umbilical cord present at the cervix.
- The curvature of the foetal spine is oriented downward (also called "back down" or dorsoinferior), and the foetal shoulder presents at the cervix.

\section*{Possible causes}
- Grand multiparity
- Uterine malformation
- Twin pregnancy
- Prematurity
- Placenta praevia
- Foeto-pelvic disproportion
- Pendulous abdomen
- Polyhydramnios
- Pelvic inlet contracture and / or foetal macrosomia
- Uterine abnormalities (e.g. bicornuate uterus or uterine fibroids)
- Foetal anomaly (e.g. tumours of the neck or sacrum, hydrocephaly, abdominal distension)
- Poorly formed lower segment
- Wrong dates (i.e. more premature than appears)

\section*{Associated risk factors}
- Cord presentation or prolapse if membranes rupture or at the onset of labour
- foetal hypoxia if left unattended in labour
- Shoulder presentation and transverse lie in labour
- Uterine rupture

\section*{Diagnosis}

This diagnosis should be made before labour begins, at the final prenatal visit before the birth.
The uterus is very wide: the transverse axis is virtually equivalent to the longitudinal axis; fundal height is less than 30 cm near term

\section*{On examination:}
- Head in one side, breech in the other.
- Vaginal examination reveals a nearly empty true pelvis or a shoulder with-sometimes-an arm prolapsing from the vagina.

