\section*{UNSTABLE LIE OF THE FOETUS}

\section*{Introduction}

Unstable lie refers to the frequenly changing of fetal lie and presentation in late pregnancy beyond 37 weeks and impacts on labour and delivery process. At earlier gestations the fetus due to prematurity can alter their lie and presentation.

\section*{Contributing factors}
- High parity
- Pendulous abdomen
- Placenta praevia
- Polyhydramnios
- Pelvic inlet contracture and / or fetal macrosomia
- Uterine abnormalities (e.g. bicornuate uterus or uterine fibroids).
- Foetal anomaly (e.g. tumours of the neck or sacrum, hydrocephaly, abdominal distension)
- Distended maternal urinary bladder > Poorly formed lower segment
- Wrong dates (i.e. more premature than appears)
- Undiagnosed twins

\section*{Management}

Diagnosis: Usually made when a varying foetal lie is found on repeated clinical examination in the last month of pregnancy.

\section*{General principles}
- $85 \%$ of foetal lies will become longitudinal before rupture of the membranes or labour I
- Abdominal palpation to assess for polyhydramnios
- Pelvic examination as indicated (assess pelvic size and shape)
- Ultrasound to exclude mechanical cause
- Inform woman of need for prompt admission to hospital if membranes rupture or when labour starts
- Hospital admission from 37 weeks onwards is recommended
- Immediate clinical assistance if membranes rupture or signs of labour
- May attempt external version to cephalic presentation in early labour with access to facilities for immediate delivery if indicated
- If cephalic presentation is maintained (spontaneously or otherwise) manage as normal

\section*{Intrapartum management}

If SROM occurs, perform vaginal examination to exclude the presence of a cord or malpresentation.

\section*{Vaginal and pelvic assessment}
- Establish presentation
- Exclude cord presentation
- Assess if polyhydramnios
- Assess cervical dilatation

\section*{If the lie is longitudinal:}
- Normal labour management.

