\section*{SHOULDER DYSTOCIA}

\section*{Introduction}

The overall incidence of shoulder dystocia varies based on fetal weight, occurring in 0.6 to 1.4 percent of all infants with a birth weight of $2,500 \mathrm{~g}$ to $4,000 \mathrm{~g}$, increasing to a rate of 5 to 9 percent among fetuses weighing 4,000 to $4,500 \mathrm{~g}$ born to mothers without diabetes. However, most cases occur in fetuses of normal birth weight and are not anticipated, limiting the clinical usefulness of risk-factor identification. Shoulder dystocia occurs with equal frequency in primigravid and multigravid women ${ }^{7}$.

\section*{Definition}

Shoulder dystocia is the failure of the shoulders to spontaneously deliver following delivery of the baby's head due to impaction of the shoulders behind the symphysis pubis'.

