- Chills
- Fever
- Hypotension
- Mental confusion
- Tachycardia
- Tachypnea
- Severe septic shock
- Cool clammy skin
- Bradycardia
- Cyanosis

\section*{Management of septic shock 6,9, II}

It consists of two major phases:

\section*{Restoration of circulatory function and oxygenation}
- Volume replacement: Blood transfusion, if not available crystalloids and colloids can be used. The CVP measurement is critical to guard against circulatory overload.
- Corticosteroids such as:
- Hydrocortisone Igm IV every 6 hours or,
- Dexamethasone 20 mg initially followed by $200 \mathrm{mg} /$ day by IV infusion.
- $\beta$-adrenergic stimulants: isoprenaline cause arteriolar dilatation, increase heart rate and stroke volume improving tissue perfusion. Blood volume must be normal prior to its administration.
- Supplemental oxygen: if respiratory function is impaired.
- Aminophylline: improves respiratory function by alleviating bronchospasm.
- Eradication of infection

