\section*{COMPLICATIONS OF LABOR PROLONGED LABOUR}

\section*{Introduction}

Prolonged labour is often defined as onset of regular, rhythmical painful contractions accompanied by cervical dilation where labour is longer than 24 hours. This definition however has limitations, and therefore it is more useful in terms of management to refer to prolonged stage of labour, i.e. "prolonged latent phase of labour" or "prolonged active phase of labour". Latent phase being the onset of regular painful contractions with cervical dilation up to 4 cm , and should not be longer than 8 hours.

Prolonged active phase: is regular painful contractions with cervical dilation of more than 4 cm should not last longer than 12 hours without full assessment in a facility able to offer management and treatment of complications.

\section*{Recommendation}
- Correct use and interpretation of Partograph during labour
- Prompt decision making
- Education to mothers to seek prompt skilled delivery

\section*{Causes}

Causes of prolonged labour It is usual to describe this as due to the three "Ps":
Power: poor or uncoordinated uterine action
Passenger: fetal head too large or position abnormal -, malpresentation, malposition, fetal anomalies e.g., hydrocephalus

Passage: pelvis abnormal, or tumour or obstruction in pelvis or birth canal.

\section*{Management}

\section*{Diagnosis}

Findings from history and physical examination or as interpreted from the Partograph that is correctly charted will guide in the diagnosis of prolonged labour.
a) History

Key points to note:
- At what time did the contractions begin?
- How frequent are the contractions?
- When did the membranes (water) break?

\section*{b) Examination}
- Monitor maternal vital signs
- The frequency, duration and intensity of the contractions
- Determine the foetal position and identify any evidence of cephalopelvic disproportion and /or foetal malposition
- Evaluate foetal heart rate
- Determine whether the mother's bladder is full.
- Inspect the external genitalia to determine the presence of liquid and /or blood vaginal exam with sterile gloves every four hours (or at a different frequency when indicated.
c) Investigations
- Blood grouping and cross match two units
- Urine for albumin, sugar, acetone
- Cardiotocography for assessment of fetal well-being

\section*{Treatment}
a) Supportive
- Monitor maternal vital signs at the following intervals
- Temperature 2-4 hourly,
- Pulse $1 / 2$ hourly,
- Respirations 4 hourly
- Blood Pressure 4 hourly
- Monitor foetal heart rate $1 / 2$ hourly but in case of non-reassuring fetal status , I/4 hourly
- Measure maternal urine volume- should be $30 \mathrm{mls} /$ hour every $2-4$ hours
- Ensure that the bladder is emptied frequently to allow descent of the fetal head- Encourage the woman to empty the bladder frequently. If not able to pass urine, catheterization should be attempted.
- Start IV fluids-Normal saline or ringer's lactate if there is shock if no shock give ringers lactate continue during transfer or referral
- If signs of infection, give broad-spectrum antibiotics - IV Ceftriaxone or Crystapen
- Encourage change of position or ambulation
- Oxygen by mask if applicable
b) Definitive treatment

\section*{First stage}

Consider augmentation if malpresentation and obstruction have been ruled out and based on parity.

\section*{Second stage}
- Maternal expulsive efforts increase fetal risk by reducing the delivery of oxygen to the placenta. While spontaneous maternal "pushing" should be allowed, prolonged effort and holding the breath should not be encouraged. If malpresentation and obvious obstruction have been ruled out, labour should be augmented with oxytocin
- Consider Vacuum extraction if fetal head is less than 1/5 palpable per abdomen and the woman is fully dilated
- If fetal head is more than $2 / 5$ th palpable, deliver by Caesarean section

\section*{Third Stage}

Perform active management of the third stage of labour.
If no progress and unable to manage, consider referral to a comprehensive EOC facility.

\section*{Referral process}
- Explain the dangers of prolonged labour to the family
- Write a referral note and refer immediately to the hospital indicating the management offered
- A skilled health care provider must escort the woman and continue to monitor her condition.

