\section*{Introduction}

Obstructed labour is the arrest of vaginal delivery of the foetus due to mechanical obstruction.
Obstructed labour means that, in spite of strong contractions of the uterus, the fetus cannot descend through the pelvis because there is an insurmountable barrier preventing its descent. Obstruction usually occurs at the pelvic brim, but occasionally it may occur in the cavity or at the outlet of the pelvis. Obstructed labour causes significant maternal morbidity in the short term notably infection and long term notably obstetric fistulas and stress incontinence. Globally obstructed labour accounts for $9 \%$ of all maternal deaths

\section*{Recommendations}
- Educate all mothers on importance of ANC attendance
- Proper History taking
- Correct use and interpretation of partograph for decision making
- Emergency preparedness
- Monitoring and interpretation of observations

\section*{Aetiology}

Cephalopelvic disproportion occurs when there is a misfit between the fetal head and the pelvis. This means it is difficult or impossible for the fetus to pass safely through the pelvis.

Cephalopelvic disproportion may be due to a small pelvis with a normal size head, or a normal pelvis with a large fetus, or a combination of a large baby and small pelvis. Cephalopelvic disproportion cannot usually be diagnosed before the 37th week of pregnancy because before then the head has not reached birth size.

Cephalopelvic disproportion may be:
Marginal: In these cases, the problem may be overcome during labour. Strong uterine contractions, relaxation of the pelvic joints and moulding of the fetal skull may enable the fetus to pass through the pelvis for vaginal delivery

Definite: This occurs because the pelvis is too small, is abnormal in shape, or because the fetus is abnormal or too large for the pelvis through which it has to pass. Operative delivery will be necessary.

\section*{Risk factors}

\section*{Maternal}
- Bony obstruction due to: contracted pelvis, tumours of pelvic bones
- Soft tissue obstruction due to:
- Uterus: impacted subserous pedunculated fibroid, constriction ring opposite the neck of the foetus.
- Cervix: cervical dystocia.
- Vagina: septa, stenosis, tumours.
- Ovaries: Impacted ovarian tumours.

\section*{Fetal}
- Malpresentation and malposition: e.g.
- Persistent occipito-posterior and deep transverse arrest,
- Persistent mento-posterior and transverse arrest of the face presentation
- Brow
- Shoulder
- Impacted frank breech
- Large sized foetus (macrosomia).
- Congenital anomalies: e.g.
- Hydrocephalus
- Foetal ascites
- Foetal tumours
- Locked and conjoined twins

\section*{Outcomes}
- There are differences in the behaviour of the uterus during obstructed labour, depending on whether the woman has delivered previously. The pattern in primigravid women typically is diminishing contractility with risk of infection and fistula may result from tissue acidosis.
- In developing countries, obstetric fistulae are commonly the result of prolonged obstructed labour following from pressure necrosis caused by impaction of the presenting part during difficult labour. In the infant, neglected obstructed labour may cause asphyxia leading to stillbirth, brain damage or neonatal death.
- In parous women, contractility may be maintained with the risk of uterine rupture'. When the membranes rupture and the amniotic fluid drains away, the fetus is forced into the lower segment of the uterus by contractions. If the contractions continue, the lower segment stretches, becomes dangerously thin and is likely to rupture. However, uterine exhaustion may occur before that point is reached, causing contractions to become weaker or cease altogether and making the occurrence of uterine rupture less likely.
- Rupture of the uterus may be complete or incomplete. If it is complete i.e. the uterus communicates directly with the peritoneal cavity, bleeding will occur within the peritoneum. If it is incomplete i.e. the rupture does not reach the visceral peritoneum, bleeding will occur behind the visceral peritoneum.
- Rupture of the uterus is more likely to occur in multipara (it is very rare in nullipara), especially if the uterus is already weakened by the scar of a previous caesarean section.

Others include:
- Maternal morbidity mainly due to infection
- Haemorrhage
- Obstetric fistula
- Skeletal and Neurologic complications

\section*{Fetal}
- Non reassuring foetal status
- Birth asphyxia
- Birth Injuries

\section*{Prevention}

Strategies to avert the problem of prolonged or obstructed labour include:
- Address malnutrition in the girl child undernutrition, obesity, DM - NCD3 and communicable diseases such as TB, Polio; Micronutrient deficiencies such as vitamin D and exposure to sunlight and body height to fetal weight4
- Girl child empowerment strategies that accord her retention in education; eliminate sociocultural harmful practices such as early childbearing / teenage pregnancies; commence childbearing beyond adolescent-hood and provide socio-economic autonomy
- Correct use and interpretation of a Partograph during labour monitoring
- Prompt referral system
- Strengthen the health system: Access and coverage with comprehensive obstetric units; emergency preparedness; competent skilled birth attendance; facilities that can perform caesarean sections, vacuum delivery, symphysiotomy or provide robust referrals
- Encourage early recognition of prolonged labour and respond in a timely and appropriate manner

\section*{Management}

\section*{History}

Points to pick when taking a history include:
- prolonged labour
- frequent and strong uterine contractions
- rupture membranes

\section*{Examination}

Signs of maternal distress on general examination include:
- exhaustion
- high temperature $\left(38^{\circ} \mathrm{C}\right)$
- rapid pulse
- signs of dehydration: dry tongue and cracked lips

\section*{Abdominal examination}
- The uterus is hard and tender
- frequent strong uterine contractions with no relaxation in between (tetanic contractions)
- rising retraction ring (Bandl's ring) is seen and felt as an oblique groove across the abdomen
- foetal parts cannot be felt easily
- FHS are absent or show foetal distress due to interference with the utero-placental blood flow

\section*{Vaginal examination}
- Vulva is oedematous.
- Vagina is dry and hot
- Cervix is fully or partially dilated, oedematous and hanging
- The membranes are ruptured
- Presence of meconium stained, foul smelling liquor. Though based on the duration prior to presentation, liquor may be absent
- The presenting part: is high and not engaged or impacted in the pelvis. If it is the head it shows excessive moulding and large caput.

\section*{Diagnosis}
- Unsatisfactory progress that results in prolonged labour can be the earliest sign of obstructed labour.
- It is the clinical picture of obstructed labour with impending rupture uterus (excessive uterine contraction and retraction).

\section*{Differential diagnosis}
- Constriction ring
- Fundal myoma
- Full bladder

\section*{Prediction}
- Various predictive tools that include maternal height, shoe size, external and internal pelvimetry, safe, low-cost, easy-to-use 3D camera platform2 and ultrasound have been used to predict obstructed labour but are inconclusive.
- So far, the best predictor is the labour processes. Include the description of Normal Mechanisms of labour in relation to the type of pelvis. When curtailed i.e. flexion, internal rotation, extension. external rotation, restitution result in prolonged labour or obstructed labour.

\section*{Treatment}

\section*{Supportive management}
- Resuscitate the mother: rapid assessment of airway, breathing and circulation and manage as appropriate
- Rehydrate the patient: Aim is to maintain the normal plasma volume and to prevent or treat dehydration and ketosis. Put two wide bore needle or cannulas. If the woman in shock give intravenous fluids e.g. normal saline I litre in the first I 15 minutes or as quickly as possible. If the woman is mainly starved and exhausted, give I-2 litres or 10\% dextrose 6 hours
- Catheterize: insert an indwelling urinary catheter using aseptic technique and monitor urine output . An indwelling catheter also prevent obstetric fistula
- Give antibiotics:

If there are signs of infection, or membranes have been ruptured for 18 hours or more or the period of gestation is 37 weeks or less provide antibiotics as:
1. Ampicillin $2 g$ every 6 hours and
2. Gentamicin $5 \mathrm{mg} /$ body weight IV for every 24 hours
3. If the woman delivered by $\mathrm{c} / \mathrm{s}$ continue antibiotics and give Metronidazole 500 mg IV every 8 hours until the woman fever free for 48 hours

\section*{Definitive management}
- Delivery of the baby
- Caesarean section is the safest method even if the baby is dead as labour must be immediately terminated and any manipulations may lead to rupture uterus ${ }^{5}$.
- Cephalo- pelvic disproportion
- If cephalo- pelvic disproportion is confirmed, prior to onset of labour deliver by elective caesarean section. If the mother in established labour, then deliver by emergency caesarean section
- If the fetus dead- delivery by craniotomy. If not possible, deliver by caesarean section.
- Obstruction
- If the fetus is alive, the cervix is fully dilated and the head is at 0 station or below deliver by vacuum extraction
- If the fetus is alive and the cervix is not fully dilated or if the fetal head too high for vacuum extraction, referral or perform immediately emergency caesarean section

\section*{Referral process}
- Write referral note and refer immediately to a health facility with comprehensive Obstetric care
- Important to use the hotline communication to alert the facility of referral to of the patient being transferred
- Empathetic Communication with the patient and the relatives on the patient's condition and risks that necessitate the referral MUST be provided
- A skilled health provider MUST accompany the patient and monitor her condition
- First aid measures (supportive) must have been instituted and continued on her transit to the next health facility
- Maternal vital signs are monitored I/2/ hourly
- Fetal heart rate monitored $1 / 2$ hourly
- Ensure IV fluids $\mathrm{n} /$ saline or dextro- saline is continued during the transfer
- Commence parenteral antibiotics (Ampicillin 500 mg , Gentamicin 80 mg and Flagyl 500 mg stat) ${ }^{8}$

\section*{Complications}

\section*{Maternal:}
- Maternal distress and ketoacidosis.
- Rupture uterus.
- Necrotic vesico-vaginal fistula.
- Infections as chorioamnionitis and puerperal sepsis.
- Postpartum haemorrhage due to injuries or uterine atony.

\section*{Foetal:}
- Asphyxia.
- Intracranial haemorrhage from excessive moulding.
- Birth injuries.
- Infections.

