\section*{RUPTURED UTERUS}

\section*{Introduction}
- Uterine rupture is an important complication occurring particularly during intra partum period and a major contributor of abnormal uterine bleeding contributing to maternal and new-born morbidity and mortality.
- Ruptured uterus is catastrophic and associated with high maternal and perinatal morbidity and mortality.
- The health system must be robust to provide for emergency care and referral mechanisms to undertake caesarean section, laparotomy, hysterectomy, blood transfusion and accord a multidisciplinary approach to patients with this complication.'
- Most of the ruptured uterus in LMIC occur because of cephalo-pelvic disproportion and obstructed labour. Additionally, there is need to address the three delay model ${ }^{2}$ such as promoting health seeking behavior during antenatal period; emergency preparedness; discourage cultural practice of home delivery without skilled birth attendants or unplanned VBAC; provide better transport and referral systems; improve obstetric competences and health care management of women in labour.

\section*{Epidemiology}

Uterine rupture is rare occurring below $1 / 1000$. The prevalence of uterine rupture for previous Caesarean section is in the region of $1 \%$ in the developed countries, while in women without previous $\mathrm{C} / \mathrm{S}$ is less than $1 / 10,000$. ${ }^{19}$

About $6 \%$ of babies do not survive their mothers' uterine ruptures. Only about $1 \%$ of mothers die due to complications. Prompt diagnosis of uterine rupture increases the chances of the mother and the baby's survival.

\section*{Recommendations}
- Capacity building - impacting relevant skills
- Timely referral services from lower level to higher level
- Functional operation theatre
- Availability of blood and blood products
- Promotion of pregnant mothers to attend ANC
- Discourage harmful practices

\section*{Definition}

Rupture of the uterus occurs when the integrity of the myometrium is breached. This can be complete with extrusion of the uterine content into the abdomen or extension into the bladder and broad ligament. In incomplete (partial) the uterus has dehiscence with the uterine content held within by the serosal layer.

\section*{Risk factors for uterine rupture}
- Previous uterine scar; C/S, myomectomy scar
- Prior uterine rupture
- Cephalo-pelvic disproportion
- Prolonged/obstructed labour
- Malpositions
- malpresentations
- Multi-parity
- Prior uterine manipulation: MVA, D\&C

\section*{Injudicious use of uterotonics for induction and augmentation of labour}

Uterine rupture is the most serious complication for women undergoing trial of labour (TOL) after prior caesarean delivery.

While rates of uterine rupture vary significantly according to a variety of clinically associated risk factors, the absolute risk for this complication ranges.

Previous vaginal delivery and prior successful vaginal birth after caesarean delivery confers the lowest risk of rupture on women attempting TOLAC.

In contrast, the risk increases with cephalopelvic disproportion, prolonged labour, obstructed labour, multiple prior caesareans, multiparity, a short inter-pregnancy interval, congenital uterine anomalies, single layer uterine closure, classic caesarean scar, prior preterm caesarean, foetal malpresentation or malposition, uterine instrumentation, intrauterine manipulations (fundal pressure, external podalic version, internal podalic version, breech extraction, shoulder dystocia, manual removal of adherent placenta). Others include labour induction, augmentation of labour, obesity; previous history of ruptured uterus and trans-mural scar from procedures like myomectomy

Counselling of mothers with the aforementioned risk factors must be provided with an individual birth plan having discussed the benefits and risks of VBAC or elective caesarean section. Further, inform the mothers they have a high-risk pregnancy and their need to deliver under skilled birth attendance optimizing their care if she opts for TOLAC to predict, diagnose and provide immediate interventions.

\section*{Prevention strategies}
- Preventive strategies for reduction of teenage pregnancies ${ }^{3,4}$
- One previous scar mother needs to make informed choice and plan for subsequent pregnancy
- Avoiding unnecessary caesarean section ${ }^{5}$
- Adherence to the 12 steps to Safe and Respectful Mother Baby-Family Maternity Care ${ }^{6}$
- Avoid injudicious use of Misoprostol and oxytocin in induction and augmentation of labour ${ }^{7}$
- Promotion of mothers to attend comprehensive prenatal contacts
- Promotion of skilled birth attendance ${ }^{8}$
- Competent skilled healthcare provider to predict, detect and treat parturient with uterine rupture
- Supportive health system and referral mechanism for comprehensive obstetric and emergency care
- Proper history taking
- Proper pelvic assessment for adequacy
- The only way to prevent uterine rupture is proper use of partograph and prompt interpretation and action.
- Misuse of uterotonics
- Timely referral
- Patient education on importance

\section*{Prediction}

Prediction modelling of individual risk for uterine rupture is not accurate for patients before admission or soon after admission with trial of labour with one previous scar. ${ }^{9}$ Sonographic evaluation of the lower uterine segment thickness provides a better risk assessment for uterine rupture following labour in previous caesarean section. However, evidence is variable in cut off due to lack of standardized technique in measurement of myometrial thickness. ${ }^{10,11,12}$

The most consistent early indicator of uterine rupture is the onset of a prolonged, persistent, and profound foetal bradycardia.

