\section*{Types of uterine tears}

\section*{Rupture through cervix and vagina}
- If the uterus is torn through the cervix and vagina, mobilize the bladder at least 2 cm below the tear.
- If possible, place a suture $I$ cm below the upper end of the cervical tear and keep traction on the suture to bring the lower end of the tear into view as the repair continues.

\section*{Rupture laterally through uterine artery}
- If the rupture extends laterally to damage one or both uterine arteries, ligate the injured artery.
- Identify the arteries and ureter prior to ligating the uterine vessels.

\section*{Rupture with broad ligament hematoma}
- If the rupture has created a broad ligament hematoma, clamp, cut and tie off the round ligament.
- Open the anterior leaf of the broad ligament.
- Drain off the hematoma manually, if necessary.
- Inspect the area carefully for injury to the uterine artery or its branches. Ligate any bleeding vessels.

\section*{Management}

\section*{Clinical findings}

\section*{Complete uterine rupture}
- Severe abdominal pain
- Sign of hypovolemic shock
- Abdominal tenderness
- Foetal body under abdominal wall
- Absence of foetal heart
- Vaginal bleeding

\section*{Incomplete uterine}
- Mild symptoms and signs
- Haematoma in broad ligaments

\section*{Diagnosis}

This can be non -specific commonly seen with uterine dehiscence. With uterine rupture foetal non reassuring status often with bradycardia or demise; maternal sudden bleeding and excruciating lower abdominal pain, shock or demise also reported.

On physical examination uterine hypertonicity is followed by uterine quiescence or poor progress of labour, Bandl ring formation, tenderness in the lower uterine segment to extrusion of foetal parts and placenta into the abdomen felt just under the anterior abdominal wall. Upon vaginal assessment the foetal part is felt higher up and not next to the cervix and may also feel a breached lower uterine segment.

\section*{Differential Diagnosis}
- Placenta praevia
- Abruptio placentae
- Extra uterine pregnancy
- Ruptured spleen or liver
- Acute abdomen in pregnancy.

\section*{Intervention}

The timing of the uterine rupture to institution of definitive management is crucial. Definitive therapy for the foetus is delivery and must generally be accomplished with alacrity to avoid major foetal morbidity and mortality.

Studies show the foetus must be delivered in 10-37 minutes. ${ }^{13,14,15,16}$ Conversely, therapy for the mother can generally be supportive and resuscitative until surgical intervention can be undertaken to arrest the often-life-threatening uterine haemorrhage.

\section*{Management principles for uterine rupture}
- Immediate stabilization of the mother
- Delivery of the foetus through caeserian section
- Urgent mobilization of the resources: such as personnel, emergency services, blood, immediate theatre access
- After the foetus is delivered, assessment intra-operatively of the uterine rupture make note of:
- Type of uterine rupture
- Extent of uterine rupture
- Degree of haemorrhage
- General condition of the mother
- Mother's desire for future childbearing

\section*{Repairing the uterine tear}
- Repair the tear with a continuous locking stitch of chromic catgut number 0 (or polyglycolic) suture. If bleeding is not controlled or if the rupture is through a previous classical or vertical incision, place a second layer of suture.
- Ensure that the ureter is identified and exposed to avoid including it in a stitch.
- If the woman has requested tubal ligation, perform the procedure at this time.
- If the rupture is too extensive for repair, proceed with hysterectomy.
- Control bleeding by clamping with long artery forceps and ligating. If the bleeding points are deep, use figure-of-eight sutures.
- Place an abdominal drain.
- Ensure that there is no bleeding. Remove clots using a sponge.
- In all cases, check for injury to the bladder. If a bladder injury is identified, repair the injury (see below).
- Close the fascia with continuous chromic catgut number 0 (or polyglycolic) suture.

Uterine repair can be considered in the following circumstance:
- Desire for future childbearing
- Low transverse uterine rupture
- No extension of the tear to the broad ligament, cervix, or paracolpos
- Easily controllable uterine haemorrhage
- Good general condition
- No clinical or laboratory evidence of an evolving coagulopathy

Hysterectomy should be considered the treatment of choice when intractable uterine bleeding occurs or when the uterine rupture sites are multiple, longitudinal, or low lying.

Consequences to the foetus include: foetal hypoxia/ anoxia, foetal acidosis; increased admission int NICU and early neonatal death.

Maternal consequences include: severe maternal haemorrhage; maternal hypovolemic shock; bladder injury; need for hysterectomy; admission in critical care unit and maternal death.

The following are elements that provide prognostic attributes ${ }^{17}$ :
- Debrief of patients that underwent primary caesarean section in the immediate postpartum period (its indication, type of incision, birthing experience) and planning the for the next pregnancy and its mode of delivery whether VBAC or elective caesarean section
- Screening of patients attending antenatal care -risk status for birth planning, emergency preparedness, referral and counselling provided at each antenatal visit
- The benefits and risks associated with risk status such as cephalo-pelvic disproportion or TOLAC for those with one previous scar discussed in the antenatal contacts scheduled.
- Discussion of delivery options during prenatal care and decision made with the patients by 36 weeks of gestation
- Effective communication to have skilled birth attendance and offered respectful maternity care
- Use of the partograph during labour for monitoring, decision making and appropriate interventions when dysfunctional labour or symptoms and signs of uterine rupture are detected
- High index of suspicion and emergency laparotomy with uterine rupture

\section*{Counselling for Future Pregnancies}
- If tubal ligation was not performed at the time of laparotomy, explain the increased risk of rupture with subsequent pregnancies, and discuss the option of permanent contraception.
- If the defect is confined to the lower segment the risk of rupture in a subsequent pregnancy is similar to that of someone with a previous caesarean section.
- If there are extensive tears involving the upper segment, future pregnancy may be contraindicated.
- Women with a history of uterine rupture should have a planned elective caesarean section (37 to 38 weeks' gestation) in their next pregnancy.

