\section*{OBSTETRIC FISTULA}

\section*{Introduction}

Obstetric fistula (OF) is a devastating yet often neglected injury that occurs as a result of prolonged obstructed labour. Women who experience obstetric fistula suffer constant urine/stool/fecal incontinence, shame, social segregation and health problems.

\section*{Epidemiology}

The World Health Organization has estimated that I-2 million women are affected with at least 50,000 to 100,000 cases of obstetric fistula occurring every year, and that over two million women with obstetric fistula in developing countries remain untreated ${ }^{1}$. The prevalence of obstetric fistula is approximately 1.6 per 1000 women of reproductive age in sub-Saharan Africa and 1.2 per 1000 in South Asia ${ }^{2}$. It is estimated that $1 \%$ of women in Kenya are affected by OF.

OF is a chronic condition that disrupts women's lives, because of its associated stigma and isolation. Fistula illness often introduces a crisis in women's life begetting feelings of shame and serious disruption to their social, psychological, physical and economic lives, in addition to dealing with moral, hygiene and social relationship challenges, and even early mortality.

Increasingly, these fistulas are getting more complex. There are few surgeons trained with an ever-increasing backlog of cases to be addressed and the need to have a multidisciplinary approach to provide life restoring treatment ${ }^{3}$.

Currently, women are able to access surgery and other services for Vesicovaginal and Rectovaginal fistulae (VVF/RVF) through Fistula camps held in national referral hospitals and dedicated fistula centres generating a significant pool of women who have undergone surgery and are ready to regain normal lives.

In the Campaign to End Fistula which started in 2002 politicians, health care providers, policy makers and communities need to address towards eliminating this problem, use resources on national scales, and face the reality that obstetric fistula is an issue of basic human rights ${ }^{4}$.

\section*{Recommendation}

For women in the postoperative period after the surgical repair of a simple obstetric urinary fistula (simple" fistula being defined as a mid-anterior vaginal wall fistula with minimal scarring and with a diameter of 3 cm or less.), short duration of bladder catheterization ( 7 to 10 days) is recommended as an alternative to longer duration of catheterization

\section*{Definition}

Obstetric fistula is an abnormal opening or hole between a woman's genital tract and her urinary tract and/or rectum that is caused by prolonged obstructed labour.

Obstetric labour injury complex is a broad range of injuries a patient with obstetric fistula suffers including: - vesical-vaginal fistula, recto-vaginal fistula, ureteric fistulae, renal damage, vaginal stenosis, damage to the cervix, nerve damage, bone damage-pubic bone osteitis, urine dermatitis, depression, divorce/separation, amenorrhoea, infertility, malnutrition, poor reproductive outcomes and bladder stones.

\section*{Causes of obstetric fistula}
- Prolonged and Obstructed labour is the main cause of Obstetric fistula
- Other causes: -
- Destructive delivery
- Instrumental vaginal delivery
- Caesarean delivery with or without hysterectomy
- Harmful Traditional practices e.g. when defibulation is necessary before surgery due to previous FGM
- Symphysiotomy

\section*{Causes of non-obstetric fistula}
- Traumatic
- Coitus
- Sexual violence (forceful intercourse or introduction of objects into the vagina)
- FGM
- Accidental trauma e.g., falling on a stick
- Infection- granulomatous infection, TB, HIV
- Malignancy (especially advanced cervical cancer)
- latrogenic (during Gynaecological surgery)
- Radiotherapy

\section*{Pathogenesis of Obstetric Fistula}

The most common cause of obstetric fistula is prolonged obstructed labour
When labour is obstructed, there is prolonged pressure on the anterior vaginal wall and underlying bladder neck or urethra as the tissues are compressed between the foetal head and posterior aspect of the symphysis pubis reducing the blood supply and leading to ischaemic necrosis of the soft tissue.

After delivery of the (usually stillborn) baby, the necrotic tissue sloughs off, allowing a direct communication of the genital tract (Uterus, cervix, vagina) with the urinary tract (ureters, urinary
bladder, urethra) and/ or GIT (usually the rectum or anus, anal sphincter). The sloughing process takes place over a few days to weeks.
