- Examine other systems to rule out inter-current infections and comorbidities such as LRTIs, DVT, hypertension, cardiac disease.
- The completed comprehensive evaluation then determines the patient management approach.

\section*{Investigations}

\section*{Laboratory tests}
- Full haemogram - For assessment of any underlying comorbidities i.e. anaemia, infections and also as a pre-operative prerequisite test
- GXM- if anaemic and for transfusion if excessive bleeding occurs intra-operatively
- Coagulation profile
- Urinalysis for assessment of urinary tract infections
- UEC- For kidney function assessment
- Triple serology (HIV, Hepatitis B \&C) - If zero-reactive needs to be addressed to improve healing
- VDRL

\section*{Imaging tests}
- Cystoscopy can be useful to better understand the location of the tract in small fistula with retracted bladder and also to rule out bladder stone or malignancies.
- Kidneys ultrasonography is a quick and useful test to detect hydronephrosis secondary to ureteral involvement in fistula patients.
- Micturating cystourethrogram
- Intravenous urogram- For assessment of any dilated renal tracts as a consequence to the fistula
- CXR- to rule TB

\section*{Management}

\section*{Immediate care at diagnosis of VVF}
- Continuous bladder drainage with Foley's catheter for I month. 20-40\% of small fistulae may heal on catheterization alone
- Removal of loose slough and necrotic tissue in the vagina
- Correction of anaemia and nutrition by giving haematinics, high protein diet for better wound healing
- Skin care- frequent washes, zinc oxide
- High fluid intake $4-51 /$ day
- Early repair when tissues are healthy

\section*{Principles of surgical repair of $\mathrm{VVF}^{12}$}

OF repair should be done by a medical professional with specialist skills in OF in an appropriate facility usually levels 4-6 facilities. The overriding principle is that the first attempt at repair offers the best chance of success which is why emphasis is placed on determining the classification of the fistula in order to decide who should operate
- Adequate exposure to ensure surgical access e.g. by labial retraction, episiotomy
- Protection of the ureters by identification and catheterisation
- Mobilization of the vagina by ensuring adequate dissection to achieve tension free closure
- Dye test to ensure water tight closure and rule out another fistula
- Continuous bladder drainage postoperative

\section*{Basic principles of repair of RVF ${ }^{12}$}

The basic principles of repair of RVF Are similar to those given for VVF except:
- Care should be taken not to cause an inadvertent stricture of the rectum.
- Preoperative bowel preparation should be more thorough than for VVF alone. This can be achieved by the use of enemas.
- A temporary colostomy may be required for large, high or severely scarred RVF.
- A previous failed repair may also require a colostomy.
- RVF repair requires prophylactic antibiotic coverage to prevent intra-operative infection.
- Postoperative women who have had an RVF repair that has not required a colostomy, should remain on a fluids-only diet for the first two days and then a low-residual diet but with a high fluid intake for a few more days.

NB: Combined fistula Combined vesico- and recto-vaginal fistula should be repaired at the same time, usually commencing with the vesico-vaginal fistula

\section*{Postoperative care}

Skilled post-operative care is key in determining the success of obstetric fistula repair

\section*{The immediate postoperative period}
- Check vital signs (blood pressure, pulse and temperature) regularly
- Indwelling urinary catheter to promote continuous urine drainage and to allow tension-free healing of the surgical scar
- Monitor for excessive blood loss both vaginally and through the catheter.
- Intravenous fluids $4-5 \mathrm{I} /$ day should be given until fluids can be taken orally.
- The fluid balance should be regularly monitored, including both fluid input and output.
- Adequate analgesia.
- Mobilized as soon as possible if she has had a simple repair.

\section*{After 24 hours and during the following days:}
- Apply the 3D principle of Drinking, Dryness and Drainage
- The woman should be encouraged to maintain a high oral-fluid intake level 4 to 5 L of fluid to enable her to produce 2 to 3 litres of urine per 24 hours. (Drinking)
- Monitor for urine leakage/bleeding (Dryness)
- Maintain continuous drainage with a Foleys catheter size 16-18F (Drainage)
- For women in the postoperative period after the surgical repair of a simple obstetric urinary fistula, short duration of bladder catheterization ( 7 to 10 days) is recommended as an alternative to longer duration of catheterization ${ }^{2}$
- The vaginal pack, if used, should be removed within 24 to 72 hours depending on the Post Op instructions.

\section*{Discharge instructions}
- To abstain from sex for at least 6 months.
- All other future deliveries to be by elective caesarean section.
- Offer family planning and adequate birth spacing counselling

\section*{Bowel care}
- Ensure a Soft diet with plenty of roughage
- Prevent constipation and undue straining
- Drugs may be used to soften the stool
- Rectal suppositories should be avoided if the client had a recto-vaginal fistula repair

\section*{Ambulation}
- Pelvic floor exercise post OF repair
- Clients done simple repairs encourage to mobilize within a day of surgery.
- For complicated repairs or ureteric re-implantation delay mobilization as per patients comfort
- In limb contractures, foot drop, or nerve damage, clients get a specialized physiotherapy program
- Prevention of deep-vein thrombosis and pulmonary complications.
- Deep-breathing exercises, coughing , Positioning
- Mobilization as soon as possible, preferably on the first postoperative day

\section*{Prognostic factors which will determine outcome of surgery}
- Size of the fistula
- Scarring
- Involvement of the closing mechanism
- Concurrent RVF
- Skill of surgeon
- Previous repair
- Medical disorders e.g. HIV, poorly controlled diabetes
- Health of the tissues around the fistula
- Circumferential defect or not
- Age of patient

\section*{Postoperative complications and their management ${ }^{12}$}
- Catheter blockage-unblock catheter or change
- Bleeding-vaginal packing, EUA and ligation of bleeding vessel
- Repair breakdown-immediate repair if within 5 days post-operative, catheterization for 1 month, repeat repair after 3 months
- Tied ureters-undo the repair
- Urinary retention- self catheterization
- Post repair stress incontinence-pelvic floor exercises, stress operations, urethral plugs
- Bladder stone- surgical extraction
- Vaginal stenosis-vaginoplasty
- Urethral stenosis- urethral dilatation
- Injured ureter-reimplantation

\section*{Long-term post-operative clinical problems may include ${ }^{12}$}
- Residual incontinence, either due to the breakdown of the repair or the persistence of vesicovaginal fistula, genuine urinary stress incontinence, detrusor over-activity or mixed incontinence- physiotherapy treatment strategies for urge and stress incontinence. Cases due to failed repair will require surgical intervention.
- Urethral or vaginal strictures.
- A genuinely failed repair.
- Dyspareunia.
- Haematometra
- Secondary amenorrhoea or infertility.
- Bladder stones.

