\section*{POST ABORTION CARE}

\section*{Introduction}

Unsafe abortion is one of the big five contributors to maternal mortality with an estimated contribution of around $13 \%{ }^{4}$. A woman is more likely to die from unsafe abortion related complications in the African continent as compared to other regions. ${ }^{\underline{3}}$

According to Dragoman et al (10), severe maternal outcomes related to abortion are mostly encountered in women between the ages $20-34$. Increased mortality rates are seen in women who undertake abortion at gestational ages of > 14 weeks with no support systems. Hemorrhage is the most common cause of severe maternal outcomes; however, infection (alone and in combination with hemorrhage) is the most common cause of death.

In Kenya, unsafe abortion is a major social and public health problem ${ }^{17}$. A nationwide research showed that about half a million induced abortions-unsafe for the most part-occurred in the country in 2012, corresponding to an abortion ratio of 48 abortions per 1,000 women of reproductive age ${ }^{18}$. In Kenya, Abortion contributes to $13 \%$ of maternal mortality.

The strain put on the health care system in terms of cost cannot be understated since studies have shown the cost implications associated with management of unsafe abortion related complications both at the global level and on a study carried out in Kenya ${ }^{\underline{6}, 7}$

\section*{Definition}

Early pregnancy loss: is the loss of pregnancy whether spontaneous or by induction before viability outside the woman's womb.

Medically early pregnancy loss is interchangeably used with abortion
Abortion: The loss of a pregnancy, whether spontaneously or by induction, before viability outside the mother's womb

Abortion can be further classified as spontaneous or induced
Unsafe abortion-is defined as a procedure meant to terminate a pregnancy carried out by either person lacking the necessary skill or in an environment that does not conform to the minimal medical standards or both. $\underline{2}, \underline{11}$

\section*{Classification}

Threatened Abortion: Pregnancy related bloody vaginal discharge or frank bleeding during the first half of pregnancy without cervical dilatation. WHO, May 2019
- Inevitable abortion: The Cervix has dilated, but products of conception have not been expelled
- Complete abortion: Complete expulsion of all products of conception
- Incomplete abortion: Parts of the products of conception are retained in the uterus
- Missed abortion: Occurs when the embryo/foetus has died in the uterus but a miscarriage has not yet occurred
- Septic abortion: Abortion associated with infection of the products of conception and endometrial lining of the uterus leading to generalized infection

\section*{Risk factors for spontaneous abortion}

The majority of spontaneous abortions occur early in pregnancy with approximately $80 \%$ occurring in the first trimester. In many cases, there is no specific factor that causes a spontaneous abortion.

However, more than half of first trimester spontaneous abortions are due to abnormal embryological development.

Other possible factors include: febrile illnesses, systemic and genital infections such as syphilis, systemic tuberculosis, Chagas disease, rubella virus, cytomegalovirus, herpes simplex virus, chlamydia, mycoplasma, toxoplasma gondii, listeria, brucella, maternal chronic disease, hormonal causes, environmental toxins, dietary causes, anatomic abnormalities, and pregnancy occurring while an IUD is in place.

\section*{Consequences of unsafe abortion $8.9 .10,11,12,13,14$}
- Loss of fertility- This can be as a result of complications that may necessitate hysterectomies, Asherman syndrome and Sheehan syndrome.
- Psychosocial disorders i.e. depression as a result of guilty feelings
- Disability
- Systemic Inflammatory Response Syndrome
- Maternal mortality
- Excessive additional costs to the health system and community

\section*{Prevention of unsafe abortion ${ }^{7,15,16}$}

This is aimed at:
- Reducing the number of unintended pregnancies thereby preventing the etiological agent predisposing women to unsafe abortion
- Provision of post abortion care to avert maternal morbidity and mortality from unsafe abortion complications
- Counseling and provision of contraception/ family planning services as integral to post abortion care
- Community engagement and networking
- Health facilities conducting of monitoring and evaluation of post abortion care services

\section*{Post Abortion Care}

PAC is an obstetric emergency and the patient should be stabilized.
Triage the patient and assess for shock and any emergency situation and manage

\section*{Initial assessment}
- The purpose of the initial assessment is to assess for immediate life-threatening complications i.e. shock, severe vaginal bleeding, infection/ sepsis or intra-abdominal injury.
- Inform patient/ client what you are going to do.
- Address these complications immediately if present.

\section*{Complete clinical assessment}
- History- Get the following information (from the woman or the accompanying person)
- Period of amenorrhea (LNMP) to establish the gestational age
- Bleeding- Duration, amount, color, presence of any clots
- Abdominal pain- Site, onset of pain, character of the pain, radiation of the pain (shoulder pain?), associated factors, timing (constant or intermittent), exacerbating, relieving factors, severity of the pain
