\section*{POST-PARTUM HEMORRHAGE}

\section*{Epidemiology}

Approximately $30 \%$ of maternal deaths worldwide are due to hemorrhage mostly in the immediate postpartum period. ${ }^{\text {I }}$, 19

The global prevalence of PPH is $6 \%$ and the highest burden is experienced in low-income countries. The magnitude of PPH in sub-Saharan Africa is high at $10.5 \% .^{7}$

Kenya has a Maternal Mortality Ratio of 362 per 100,000 live births as per KDHS 2014. Obstetric hemorrhage; the leading cause of maternal deaths, accounts for $39 \%(*)$ of maternal deaths ${ }^{27}$. PPH accounts for $75 \%$ of all obstetric haemorrhage ${ }^{27}$. Other causes of maternal death include hypertensive disorders, sepsis, obstructed labor, abortion and its complications as well as other indirect causes. ${ }^{5}$

\section*{Definition}

Postpartum hemorrhage has been defined as blood loss in excess of 500 ml in a vaginal birth and in excess of 1000 ml in a cesarean delivery. For clinical purposes, any blood loss that has the potential to produce hemodynamic instability should be considered PPH. Clinical estimates of blood loss are often inaccurate. ${ }^{1}$ There may be more one than definition of PPH.

