\section*{Classification}
- Primary postpartum hemorrhage: Primary (immediate) PPH occurs within the first 24 hours after delivery. Approximately $70 \%$ of immediate PPH cases are due to uterine atony. Atony of the uterus is defined as the failure of the uterus to contract adequately after delivery 1, $\underline{2}$
- Secondary postpartum hemorrhage: Secondary (late) PPH occurs between 24 hours after delivery of the infant and up to 6weeks postpartum. Most late PPH is due to retained products of conception, infection, or both. ${ }^{1,2}$

\section*{Etiology}

It may be helpful to think of the causes of PPH in terms of the 4 "T" s. More than one cause may however be present e.g., tone and tissue ${ }^{4,1,14}$
- Tone (70\%): uterine atony
- Trauma ( $20 \%$ ): uterine, cervical, or vaginal injury, uterine inversion
- Tissue ( $10 \%$ ): retained placenta (cotyledon or succenturiate lobe) or clots
- Thrombopathy (<1\%): pre-existing or acquired coagulopathy

\section*{Risk Factors}

Many women who have PPH have no identifiable risk factors ${ }^{\underline{4}}$
- Ante-Natal: maternal age above 35 years, parity $>3$, prior uterine surgery, previous PPH, uterine fibroids, pre-eclampsia, anemia, gestational diabetes, multiple pregnancy, polyhydramnios and antepartum hemorrhage
- Intrapartum: Induction of labor, prolonged $2{ }^{\text {nd }}$ stage, prolonged $3{ }^{\text {rd }}$ stage, retained placenta, instrumental vaginal birth, macrosomia, uterine rupture, general anesthesia, genital tract injuries, infection after PROM or temperature above 38 degrees Celsius

