\section*{Treatment of Primary Postpartum Hemorrhage}

Even with major advances in prevention of PPH, some women will still require treatment for excessive bleeding. Timely interventions and appropriate access, or referral and transfer to basic or comprehensive emergency obstetric care (EmONC) facilities for treatment are essential to saving the lives of women. ${ }^{1}$

All healthcare professionals should be trained on the PPH care bundles that include: readiness (preparedness), recognize, respond and review. They should refresh their knowledge and skills in emergency obstetrics on a regular basis through workshops that include didactics, practical exercises, simulations/drills and evaluations. Tracking through clinical audits and MPDSR providing for performance indicators on quality of care. ${ }^{1}$ Key to the effectiveness of treatment is early identification of hemorrhage and prompt initiation of treatment

