\section*{UTERINE ATONY}

\section*{Definition}

This refers to failure of the uterus to contract adequately. Any condition that interferes with uterine contractions will lead to an atonic uterus. ${ }^{8}$

\section*{Predisposing Factors to Uterine Atony:}
- Retained placenta, placental fragments, tissue/membranes, blood clots
- Overdistention of the uterus due to multiple gestation, excess amniotic fluid or a large baby.
- High parity.
- Prolonged labor
- Induction or augmentation of labour
- Precipitous labour (labour lasting less than 3 hours)
- Full bladder
- Uterine fibroids in pregnancy

\section*{Management of Refractory Uterine Atony (Refractory PPH)}

\section*{Definition of Refractory PPH}

This refers to the bleeding that cannot be controlled even after institution of $1^{\text {st }}$ line treatment for PPH.

Note: Before proceeding to invasive surgical procedures, WHO recommends the use of additional uterotonics, a second dose of tranexamic acid and use of intra uterine balloon tamponade.
$1^{\text {st }}$ steps in the management of Refractory PPH
- Empty bladder and insert indwelling catheter for monitoring input- output chart
- Continuous patient monitoring with MEOW chart
- Uterotonics that can be used for treatment of uterine atony
- Oxytocin infusion of 20 to 40 IU in IL normal saline at 60 drops per minute OR
- Repeat i.m Ergometrine 0.5 mg (if not $\mathrm{C} / \mathrm{I}$ ) OR
- Misoprostol $800 \mu \mathrm{~g}$ sublingual
- Carboprost $\mathbf{0 . 2 5 m g}$ IM every 15 minutes (max 2 mg )
- NOTE I.M. Tranexamic acid Igm to be administered with SOC ${ }_{[J 56]}$ and within 3 hours of PPH episode
- Bimanual uterine compression
- Uterine balloon tamponade (UBT)
- NASG
- Aortic compression and Non - pneumatic antishock garment (used in referral of patient)
- Ensure adequate analgesia.
- Effective communication.

