\section*{Genital Tract Trauma}

Genital tract trauma i.e., Cervical or vaginal lacerations is an obstetric risk to women undergoing vaginal delivery. Bleeds from cervical or vaginal lacerations are venous in origin and may be the source of postpartum hemorrhage ${ }^{14}$.

Genital tract trauma may occur with other causes of PPH and therefore in the presence of a well contracted uterus, this possibility should be considered since it is the second commonest cause of primary postpartum hemorrhage ${ }^{3}$. Some of the causes of genital tract trauma during delivery include: Precipitous labor, assisted vaginal delivery, perineal tears particularly in Primigravida women.

The presentation may vary from patients with obvious tears, to poorly repaired episiotomies and vaginal hematomas therefore creating a paradoxical picture where clinical signs do not correlate to the amount of blood loss.

Perineal tears repair - provide adequate analgesia and effective communication. Ensure proper lighting is available.

