\section*{MATERNAL SEPSIS}

\section*{Introduction}

Maternal sepsis is a life-threatening condition defined as organ dysfunction resulting from infection during pregnancy, child birth, post abortion or post-partum (within 42 days) ${ }^{1,2,11}$

The new WHO definition of maternal sepsis aligns with the $3^{\text {rd }}$ international consensus on sepsis (2016) that lays emphasis on organ dysfunction therefore predicting in-hospital mortality ${ }^{1,2,11,12}$

Pregnancy-related infections includes genital tract infections; chorioamnionitis and endometritis, extra-genital infections such as pyelonephritis as well as other infections complicating pregnancy, delivery and the puerperium (HIV, malaria, STIs, fungal and viral infections) ${ }^{\underline{2}}$

Pregnancy and delivery predispose women to infectious complications due to immunological and physiological adaptations to pregnancy, blood loss and increased maternal activity during labor ${ }^{7}$ 11

Early recognition of sepsis is crucial. The "golden hour of sepsis" underscores the correlation between timely initiation of antibiotic treatment and outcome. Each hour delay in treatment decreases survival by $7.6 \%^{\underline{5}}$

The Global Maternal Sepsis Study (GLOSS) established that effective prevention, early diagnosis and timely management of maternal sepsis are essential factors in reducing the impact of the disease on maternal mortality. $\underline{ }^{2,11}$

Women who experience peri-partum infections are susceptible to long term complications which include: chronic pelvic pain, fallopian tube blockage and secondary infertility ${ }^{\underline{2}, \underline{6}, \underline{7}}$

The biggest challenge so far in management of maternal sepsis is the lack of standard criteria to identify women with maternal sepsis. ${ }^{\underline{2}}$

\section*{Epidemiology}

Sepsis is a major cause of maternal morbidity \& mortality especially in low- and middle-income countries it ranks $3^{\text {rd }}$ among the leading direct causes of maternal mortality and accounts for $15 \%$ of deaths. ${ }^{1,3,6}$

Globally, maternal infections before and during childbirth are associated with I million new born deaths annually. ${ }^{3,12}$

Case fatality rate for maternal sepsis remains high between $4 \%$ and $50 \%$ reported in sub-Saharan Africa and south East Asia ${ }^{3}$

\section*{Risk factors for maternal sepsis}

Several factors have been associated with increased risk of maternal peri-partum infections and these include: ${ }^{\underline{3}, \underline{6}, 7}$
- Pre-existing maternal conditions such as malnutrition, diabetes, obesity and severe anemia
- Bacterial vaginosis
- Group B streptococcal infections
- Spontaneous or provider-initiated conditions during pregnancy, labor and child birth such as cervical cerclage, premature and prolonged rupture of membranes, multiple vaginal examinations, manual removal of the placenta and caesarian section

Caesarian section is the most important risk factor in the immediate post-partum period with a 5-20-fold risk compared to vaginal delivery ${ }^{3}$

Strategies to reduce maternal peri-partum infections, their short- and long-term sequelae are directed at preventive measures where such risk factors are present. Promotion of good infection control practices both in the hospital and at home is also paramount. ${ }^{3,11}$

\section*{Prevention of maternal sepsis and maternal deaths relating to sepsis $\underline{1,3,5,8}$}

The general principles that can be employed to reduce maternal sepsis can be broadly categorized into:
- Improving access to clean water and sanitation;
- Improving access to quality care during pregnancy and birth;
- Responsible and timely access to the right medicines;
- Proper infection prevention and control in hospitals and clinics.

With this in mind, the prevention strategies can further be sub classified into Pre, Intra and Postpartum.

\section*{Pre-partum prevention}
- Promoting Antenatal clinic visits based on the 2016 WHO ANC model to improve the continuum of care during pregnancy. Also, during these visits, women should be sensitized on the danger signs of sepsis i.e. Fever, Foul smelling vaginal discharge, Abdominal pains unrelated to labor so as to enable them to seek prompt medical interventions
- Routine vaccinations such as Tetanus toxoid
- Use of insecticide treated bed nets and Intermittent prevention therapy in malaria endemic zones
- Safe abortion care
- Prevention of anaemia

\section*{Intra-partum prevention}
- Delivery in areas where there are proper infection control methods. This may involve training of Traditional Birth Attendants on appropriate puerperal care
- Digital vaginal examination at intervals of four hours for routine assessment of active stage of labor in low risk women
- Intrapartum antibiotic administration to women with group B streptococcus (GBS) colonization for prevention of early neonatal GBS infection
- Antibiotic administration for women with preterm prelabour rupture of membranes
- Routine antibiotic prophylaxis for women undergoing manual removal of the placenta
- Routine antibiotic prophylaxis is recommended for women with third or fourth degree perineal tears
- Routine antibiotic prophylaxis for women undergoing caesarian sections
- Prompt recognition and treatment of women with infections intrapartum to avoid the risk of maternal death relating to sepsis

\section*{Post-partum prevention}
- Advise women to be on the lookout for possible signs that may indicate puerperal sepsis.
- Prompt treatment of those presenting with signs of puerperal sepsis

\section*{Management}

\section*{Clinical presentation ${ }^{\mathbf{2}} \boldsymbol{,} \mathbf{8}$}

This is based on the various predisposing factors and the time at which the patient presents from the onset of symptoms.

General symptoms include:
- Constant severe abdomino-pelvic pain
- Offensive vaginal discharge
- Fever or rigors
- Diaphoresis
- Nausea and vomiting
- Urinary symptoms i.e. dysuria
- Generalized maculopapular rash
- Conjunctival suffusion
- Productive cough

\section*{Clinical signs}
- Elevated body temperatures $>38^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$ low core body temperatures $<36^{\circ} \mathrm{C}$
- Abdominal-pelvic /uterine tenderness
- Decreased capillary refill with clammy or mottled skin
- Tachycardia (heart rate greater than 110 beats $/ \mathrm{min}$ )
- Low blood pressure- systolic BP less than 90 mmHg
- Tachypnea (respiratory rate greater than 24 beats/min)
- Low oxygen saturation (less than $90 \%$ at room temperature)
- Altered mental state (confusion, decreased alertness with low scores on the Glasgow Coma Scale score)
- Reduced urinary output ( $<0.5 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg} / \mathrm{hour}$ )
- Fetal distress (fetal tachycardia, acidosis)

In severe infections, the following unusual scenarios may occur and these necessitate urgent interventions to avoid possible loss of life: ${ }^{6}$
- Septic shock
- Adult respiratory distress syndrome
- Hemolysis
- Disseminated Intravascular Coagulation
- Increasing area of cellulitis and necrosis of tissue dependent on the site of infection

\section*{The National Early Warning System (NEWSÂ² Score)Â¹3}

Developed to standardize the process of recording, scoring and responding to changes in routinely measured parameters in acutely ill patients.

Founded on the premise that early detection, timeliness and competency of the clinical response comprise a triad of determinants of clinical outcomes in people with acute illness.

It is based on a single aggregate scoring system in which a score is allocated to physiological measurements already recorded in routine practice namely: respiratory rate, oxygen saturation, systolic BP, pulse rate, level of consciousness or new confusion, temperature.

NEWS ${ }^{2}$ is superior to QSOFA (Sequential Organ Failure Assessment) in detecting sepsis with organ dysfunction.

Sepsis should be considered in any patient with a NEWS score of $>/=5$ in the presence of a known infection or symptoms and signs of infection.

