\section*{Investigations ${ }^{6,10}$}

Investigations are directed at determining the etiology and risk stratification of sepsis as well as organization of care for women in the most appropriate clinical area.

Relevant first line investigations for suspected maternal sepsis include the following:
- Blood cultures are useful in isolating the causative agent(s). At least two sets of samples from different sites are cultured before commencing antibiotic treatment. The blood samples should be taken using aseptic techniques.
- Cultures from high vaginal swabs specimens
- Urine culture: mid-stream clean-catch sample
- Urinalysis
- Blood glucose: elevations in non-diabetic patients is a possible indicator of sepsis.
- Blood gas analysis is vital in the detection of acidosis and hypoxemia if progression to septic shock is suspected.
- C-reactive protein
- Full blood count with emphasis on white blood cell count.
- Liver function tests as the source of infection may be hepatic or peri-hepatic.
- Creatinine urea and electrolytes; creatinine is elevated in severe sepsis.
- Serum lactate levels; elevated levels in sepsis point to tissue hypo perfusion and thus increased risk of mortality
- Shielded chest radiograph if pulmonary infection is suspected.
- Pelvic ultrasound if there is a suspicion of retained products of conception or a pelvic abscess
- Fetal assessment using cardiotocography and/or fetal ultrasound

\section*{Treatment of maternal sepsis $\underline{2}, \underline{3}, \underline{6}, \underline{10}$}

Treatment should be commenced as soon as possible - ideally within the first hour ('golden hour') of sepsis being suspected ${ }^{\underline{6}}$.

Empiric treatment should include fluid resuscitation, correction of hypoxia and antimicrobials (antibiotics or antivirals as appropriate). Source control, consideration of the appropriate area of care as well as venous thromboembolism prophylaxis also need to be considered.

The major steps crucial in the management include:
- Fluid resuscitation
- Intravenous antibiotic administration
- Identify and treat the source of infection
- Consider transfer to specialized care
- Regular observations of all vital signs (including temperature, pulse rate, blood pressure and respiratory rate) which should be recorded on a Modified Early Obstetric Warning Score (MEOWS) chart.

\section*{Treatment of sepsis with an unknown source/ Chorioamnionitis}

\section*{Community-acquired sepsis}
- Cefuroxime 1.5g IV every 8 hours or IV Ciprofloxacin or Levofloxacin (for patients allergic to pennicillins )
- Gentamicin $4-7 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ ( $1^{\text {st }}$ dose) ( 80 mg TDS)
- Metronidazole 500 mg IV every 8 hours

\section*{If allergic to penicillin}
- Clindamycin 600 mg IV every 8 hours PLUS
- Gentamicin $4-7 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ (I ${ }^{\text {st }}$ dose) IV ( 80 mg TDS)
- Metronidazole 500 mg IV every 8 hours

\section*{Hospital-acquired sepsis (Do an antibiotic sensitivity test)}
- Piperacillin $4 \mathrm{~g}+$ tazobactam 0.5 g IV every 8 hours or Vancomycin $25-30 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ (Loading dose) IV
- Cefuroxime 1.5g IV every 8 hours
- Gentamicin $4-7 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ (I ${ }^{\text {st }}$ dose) IV ( 80 mg TDS)
- Metronidazole 500 mg IV every 12 hours

If allergic to penicillin
- Ciprofloxacin 400 mg IV every 8 hours

If at risk of MRSA, add:
- Vancomycin $25-30 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ (Loading dose) IV

If at risk of GAS, add:
- Clindamycin 600 mg IV every 8 hours
- Intravenous immunoglobulin (IVIG) I-2g/kg up to 2 doses (IVIG is recommended for severe invasive streptococcal or staphylococcal infection if other therapies have failed).

\section*{Treatment of postpartum sepsis/endometritis ${ }^{\underline{3}}$}
- Clindamycin 600 mg IV every 8 hours
- Gentamicin $4-7 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ ( $1^{\text {st }}$ dose) IV ( 80 mg TDS)

NB: Antibiotics should be continued until afebrile for 24 hours

\section*{Timing and mode of delivery in maternal sepsis (antepartum) ${ }^{\underline{6}}$}

The timing of delivery will be determined by:
- The presence of intrauterine infection
- The nature of the maternal sepsis and response to initial resuscitation efforts
- The gestation of the pregnancy and fetal status

In case of intrauterine infection, an immediate caeserean delivery is indicated.
If there is extra uterine infection, efforts to treat maternal sepsis and prolong gestation should be considered at gestations remote from term, although it is reasonable to consider delivery in term pregnancies as a means of improving maternal resuscitation.

Fetal wellbeing should be monitored during maternal sepsis with the most gestation-appropriate method.

\section*{Complications of maternal sepsis 2.12}

\section*{Maternal complications}
- Preterm labor and delivery
- Prolonged maternal hospital stay.
- Maternal complications with end organ damage i.e. pulmonary edema, adult respiratory distress syndrome, acute renal failure, hepatic dysfunction, shock, septic emboli to other organs, myocardial ischemia, cerebral ischemia, disseminated intravascular coagulation
- Admission to High Dependent or Intensive Care Units
- Maternal death

\section*{Long-term maternal complications}
- Chronic pelvic pain
- Secondary infertility

\section*{Neonatal complications}
- Pre-term birth
- Intrauterine growth restriction
- Prolonged neonatal hospital stay
- Neonatal admission to special care or ICU or transfer after birth
- Perinatal death (stillbirth, neonatal death)

