\section*{MATERNAL NEAR MISS}

\section*{Introduction}

\section*{WHO maternal near miss approach}
- Maternal deaths are considered "the tip of the iceberg" of severe maternal morbidity represented by the maternal near miss. For every woman who dies therefore, many more will survive adverse sequelae during pregnancy, delivery or in the puerperium. Studying maternal near miss has been used as a proxy to measure quality of obstetric care ${ }^{\underline{2,6}}$
- Maternal morbidity may precede maternal deaths and therefore systematic identification and study of near miss cases provides further insight on the determinants of maternal mortality. ${ }^{6}$
- Examination of maternal near miss evaluates the quality of obstetric care and may contribute a great deal in reduction of maternal mortality. ${ }^{1,2,3,4,5,6}$
- The consistency and a set of near-miss indicators enables assessment of the quality of care provided to pregnant women. ${ }^{2}, \underline{3}, \underline{5}, \underline{6}$
- Signs of organ dysfunction that follow life-threatening conditions are used to identify maternal near misses so that the same classification of underlying causes is used for both maternal deaths and near misses. ${ }^{1,2,5,6}$
- The WHO introduced the maternal near miss tool in 2009 as a way to monitor and improve on the quality of obstetric care given to women. ${ }^{1,5,6}$
- The Maternal Near Miss tool comprises 3 groups of criteria with clinical, laboratory and management-based parameters which focus on presence of organ dysfunction. ${ }^{1,2}$

\section*{Definition}

A maternal death is defined as "the death of a woman while pregnant or within 42 days of termination of pregnancy, irrespective of the duration and site of the pregnancy, from any cause related to or aggravated by the pregnancy or its management but not from accidental or incidental causes" ${ }^{\perp, 2}$

WHO defines a near miss as "a woman who nearly died but survived a complication that occurred during pregnancy, child birth or within 42 days of termination of pregnancy" ${ }^{1,2,3,4,5,6}$

\section*{Adapted Sub-Saharan Africa MNM tool}

In the international Delphi study, existing tools were rated for applicability in Sub-Saharan Africa over a series of 3 rounds. ${ }^{1}$

Experts in maternal health from Sub-Saharan Africa rated importance of the existing WHO MNM parameters using Linkert scales and further suggested additional parameters which were adopted following acceptance by $70 \%$ of panel members. ${ }^{1}$

Of the WHO MNM parameters, all 11 clinical, 4 out of 8 laboratory and 4 out of 6 of the management- based parameters were accepted. ${ }^{\underline{2}}$

6 of the WHO MNM parameters were deemed not applicable in low resource settings and they include: $\mathrm{PaO}_{2} / \mathrm{FiO}_{2}<200 \mathrm{mmHg}$, Bilirubin $>100 \mu \mathrm{~mol} / \mathrm{l}$ or $>6.0 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{dl}, \mathrm{PH}<7 . \mathrm{I}$, Lactate $>5 \mu \mathrm{~mol} / \mathrm{l}$, dialysis for Acute Renal Failure and use of vasoactive drugs. ${ }^{1}$

8 additional parameters were suggested for inclusion into an adapted Sub-Saharan Africa MNM too. These include: uterine rupture, sepsis/severe infection, eclampsia, laparotomy other than C/S, pulmonary edema, severe malaria, severe complications of abortions and severe preeclampsia with ICU admission ${ }^{1}$

