\section*{Response Strategy}

Maternal and Perinatal death review needs to be connected to a response strategy. This involves ensuring that action points to prevent avoidable deaths are implemented at all levels:
- Community level
- Facility level
- Sub-county level
- County level
- National level

\section*{Guiding principles for response}
- Start with the avoidable factors;
- Use evidence-based approaches;
- Prioritize (based on health impact, feasibility, costs, resources, health system readiness);
- Establish a timeline (immediate, short, medium and long term);
- Decide how to monitor progress, effectiveness, impact;
- Integrate recommendations within annual health plans

\section*{Timing of response}
- Immediate response: No need to wait for aggregated data to begin implementing actions: e.g., at facility level: improve coverage \& quality of care for emergency services (24/7); at community level: transportation issues that should and can be addressed quickly.
- Periodic response: Findings from periodic reviews (e.g. quarterly) should result in more comprehensive approach to addressing key issues across multiple facilities or communities: e.g.:
- Staffing levels, knowledge, skills \& behavior
- Set up quality of care improvement process for health facilities.

\section*{Levels of Response}

Response is implemented in a cascade manner at the following levels:
- Community level
- Facility level
- Sub county level
- County level
- National level

