\section*{FEEDING THE NEWBORN}

Breast milk is the best food and breastfeeding is recommended for ALL newborns irrespective of HIV status. Breastfeeding should be discussed during all antenatal contacts emphasizing on the triple key messages of early, exclusive and prolonged breastfeeding up to 2 years.

\section*{Benefits of breastfeeding}
- Breast milk (especially Colostrum) helps build the baby's immunity
- Breastfeeding nourishes the baby and helps to keep baby warm
- Promotes bonding between mother and baby
- It promotes baby's brain development
- Better weight gain
- Reduced incidence of hypoglycaemia
- Less dehydration
- Faster gastric emptying
- It helps in expulsion of the placenta faster and involution of uterus, thus reduces bleeding
- Prevents breast engorgement
- It is possible to feed almost all low birth weight babies on their mothers' milk
- Mother's milk is especially suited for her own baby and is affordable and accessible

Breastfeeding should be initiated within the first hour of birth. Early initiation of breastfeeding ensures the baby receives colostrum, provides energy and prevents most of the breastfeeding problems. Ensure that mother is in a comfortable position then;

Show the mother how to correctly position and attach for effective suckling.

