\section*{INFECTION PREVENTION CONTROL IN A NEWBORN UNIT}

\section*{General Principles of Infection Prevention and Control}
- It is the responsibility of all health care personnel in the NBU to minimise infection
- Routine care of babies from birth onwards
- Consider everybody (mother, baby, personnel) potentially infected
- Protective clothing, gloves and masks
- Aseptic technique
- Instruments \& equipment decontamination and cleaning
- Cleaning of the neonatal unit
- Waste disposal
- Isolation or cohorting
- Overcrowding - spaces between cots \& incubators
- Adequacy of personnel
- Adequate feeding
- Traffic control: reduce human traffic flow in the unit

\section*{People as sources of infection}
- Do not allow personnel with skin infections or lesions to come into direct contact with babies
- Individuals handling the baby should observe hand hygiene.

\section*{Hand washing}

Wash hands with soap and water, but if hands are visibly clean, disinfect them using an alcoholbased hand rub;

\section*{5 Moments for Hand Hygiene}

The 5 Moments for Hand Hygiene approach defines the key moments when health-care workers should perform hand hygiene.

This evidence-based, field-tested, user-centered approach is designed to be easy to learn, logical and applicable in a wide range of settings.

This approach recommends health-care workers to clean their hands
- Before touching a patient,
- Before clean/aseptic procedures,
- After body fluid exposure/risk,
- After touching a patient, and
- After touching patient surroundings.
