\section*{ACUTE KIDNEY INJURY}

\section*{Definition}

Acute kidney injury is defined as rapid decline in kidney function resulting in abrupt increase in serum creatinine or an abrupt decrease in urine output. Creatinine rises to greater than $25 \mathrm{umol} / \mathrm{L}$ or $50 \%$ increase from previous lowest, or absolute creatinine $>100 \mathrm{umol} / \mathrm{L}$ or urine output of $>\mathrm{lml} / \mathrm{kg} / \mathrm{hr}$.

Note: A large number of AKI in the newborn may be non-oliguric

\section*{Etiology}

\section*{Prerenal causes:}
- Dehydration due to poor breastfeeding Intestinal losses
- Bleeding from trauma
- Hypoxic Ischemic encephalopathy

\section*{Intrinsic renal causes:}
- Acute Tubular Necrosis
- Drugs usage like aminoglycosides, ibuprofen Sepsis
- Hypoxic ischemic encephalopathy

\section*{Post renal causes:}
- Posterior urethral valves
- Spinal cord lesions causing neuropathic bladder

\section*{Clinical presentation}
- Urine output of less than $1 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg} / \mathrm{hr}$ in most cases.
- Edema due to fluid overload failure to lose weight in the $1^{\text {st }}$ week or rapid weight gain.
- Hypertension.

\section*{Investigations}
- Urea/Electrolytes and creatinine: showing rise in creatinine, BUN and potassium.
- Urine microscopy: urine sediment showing intrinsic kidney injury, if there is features of proteinuria and hematuria
- Urine SG if high shows prerenal cause, if SG low shows intrinsic cause.
- Urine Fractional excretion of Sodium to differentiate prerenal from intrinsic renal failure.
- Abdominal ultrasound kidney, ureters, bladder (KUB) to rule out obstructive uropathy

\section*{Management}
- The main aim in managing AKI is to maintain homeostasis while awaiting improvement in renal function, either spontaneously or while the underlying cause is being treated.
- Maintain adequate renal perfusion
- Unless contraindicated due to fluid overload or cardiac failure a baby with clinical evidence of hypovolemia and oliguria administer intravenous fluid challenge $10 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ of crystalloid solution such as normal saline over 20 to 30 minutes. This can be repeated up to three times if the baby is still hypovolemic.
- Restoration of adequate urine flow and improvement in renal function with fluid resuscitation is consistent with pre-renal disease.
- If oliguria persists despite adequate correction of pre-renal factors, give:
- Intravenous furosemide $2-5 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg} /$ dose or infusion furosemide $0.1-1 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg} / \mathrm{hr}$.
- If no response consider dialysis
- Prevent fluid overload
- Fluid volume should be restricted to insensible water loss(IWL) calculated at $400 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{m} 2$ per day or $30 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$, in addition to replacing urine, gastrointestinal and other losses. Use 5 or $10 \%$ dextrose for IWL and 5th normal saline for urine. Ensure adequate hydration.
- Do a daily weight
- Maintain normal electrolytes and acid-base status

\section*{Hyperkalemia: (See section on fluid \& electrolytes)}
- Sodium supplementation if there is renal salt wasting
- Correct severe metabolic acidosis where serum bicarbonate $<15 \mathrm{mmol} / \mathrm{L}$ or $\mathrm{pH}<7.2$ : (See
- Acid base balance)
- Hyperphosphatemia: restrict intake by using breastmilk and calcium-based phosphate binders. eg calcium carbonate
- Ensure adequate nutrition
- Dosage adjustment of medications
- Avoid further nephrotoxic insults

