\section*{LARGE FOR GESTATIONAL AGE BABY AND INFANT OF A DIABETIC MOTHER}

\section*{Definition}

This is a baby with a birth weight of more than $4.0 \mathrm{~kg} ; \mathbf{O R}$ a baby whose birth weight is above the $90^{\text {th }}$ percentile for the gestation.

\section*{Diagnosis}

Suspect or expect LGA if there is:
- History of diabetes in pregnancy
- History of previous large babies

\section*{Associated problems}

The following complications are associated with LGA babies
- Hypoglyacemia
- Birth Asphyxia
- Birth injuries
- Jaundice
- In addition, babies born of a diabetic mother are prone to Infections and Respiratory distress syndrome

\section*{Infant of a Diabetic Mother}

Neonatal metabolic complications of an Infant of a Diabetic Mother
- Hypoglycaemia
- Hypocalcaemia
- Hypomagnesaemia
- Jaundice

Hypoglycaemia occurs mostly within the first 24 hours and occasionally up to 48 hrs
Get the baseline blood glucose level.

\section*{Prevention}
1. Adequate control of diabetes in pregnancy
2. Anticipate and refer early to deliver in a health facility

\section*{Management}
- Feed within $30-60$ minutes of birth \& subsequently $2-3 \mathrm{hrly}$
- Monitor blood glucose hourly for 4 hrs

NB: If blood glucose remains low treat as for symptomatic hypoglycaemia
- Closely monitor the baby to promptly recognize the associated problems
- Manage any complications detected
- If the mother is not already diagnosed as diabetic, investigate to rule out diabetes mellitus. If confirmed positive, manage the diabetic mother or refer.

\section*{TRANSFUSIONS IN THE NEWBORN}

Haemoglobin changes in the first month
Birth $14-23 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{dl}$;
2 wks $14-19 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{dl}$;
$\underline{4 \text { wks term } 13-14 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{dl} \text {, preterm } 7-9 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{dl}}$

\section*{ANAEMIA}

Definition: $\mathrm{I}^{\text {st }}$ week $\mathrm{Hb}<\mathrm{I} 3 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{d}$; after $\mathrm{I}^{\text {st }}$ week $\mathrm{Hb}<10 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{d}$

\section*{Prevention}

Minimise iatrogenic blood loss by appropriate use of tests. Hospitals should have micro techniques for blood collection for neonates

\section*{Preterm babies}

Give prophylactic iron and folate. Start at 2 weeks till age 1 year
Erythropoietin can also be used where available.

\section*{Causes}

Early onset - $\mathbf{I}^{\text {st }} \mathbf{2}$ days postnatal age
Haemorrhage: birth trauma, internal haemorrhage, cord accidents, foetal-maternal transfusion, twin-twin transfusion

Haemolysis: blood group incompatibility, congenital infection
Management

Haemorrhage: Assess for signs of acute blood loss - shock. If present, give normal saline 15$20 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ over 10 minutes as you organise for blood transfusion. Repeat if signs persist. Transfuse as soon as blood is available $20-30 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ over 2 hrs . If no signs of shock transfuse with $20-30 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ over $2-3 \mathrm{hrs}$. At the end of the transfusion before you discard the pack re-evaluate to see if baby needs more blood. Do not give furosemide .

\section*{Use whole blood}

Haemolysis: Do blood group mother \& baby, Coombs test, reticulocyte count, bilirubin. Treat the cause; may need exchange transfusion. Give furosemide with the transfusion.

Use fresh(less than 5 days old) whole blood for exchange transfusion.
Late onset $>2$ days postnatal age

\section*{Blood loss:}

Latrogenic - Repeated laboratory investigations
Haemorrhagic disorders including DIC due to infections

\section*{Haemolysis}

Anaemia of prematurity (Usually 2-6 weeks of age)

\section*{Management}

\section*{Investigate:}

Full blood count including a peripheral blood film (PBF)for red cell morphology
Reticulocyte count
Coagulation screen if you suspect DIC
Indications for RBC transfusion $\mathrm{Hb}</ 3 \mathrm{~g} / \mathrm{d}$ if:
