\section*{HYDROCEPHALY}

This occurs when there is an unusually large head arising from blockage in the free flow of CSF in the ventricular system.

\section*{Management}
- Monitor head circumference
- Refer early for surgical CSF drainage

\section*{MANAGEMENT OF COMMON GENETIC BIRTH DEFECTS}
- Provide emotional support and reassurance to the mother
- If the baby has Down syndrome or unusual facial features, advise the parents about the long-term prognosis, and refer the family to a specialized centre for developmental evaluation and follow-up
- Refer to paediatrician for further care
- If the mother is not going to breastfeed and the mother requests for a contraceptive method, provide family planning services

\section*{Counselling:}

\section*{In all cases of birth defects:}
- Counsel parents in all cases.
- Counsel both parents at the same time wherever possible
- Have the most qualified health worker talk to parents
- Ensure honesty, sensitivity and empathy by all staff
- Parents should be shown any obvious defect on the baby and told the implications
- Current and future management to be discussed
- Link with any community support groups should be made

\section*{BLEEDING DISORDERS}

\section*{Definition}

This is when a baby presents with unusual and uncontrolled bleeding.
There may be prolonged bleeding from:
- The umbilical cord
- The Gastrointestinal tract
- Into the skin

Others areas where bleeding may occur include:
- Intracranial haemorrhage
- Pulmonary

\section*{Predisposing factors}
- Prematurity
- Infections
- Birth trauma
- Asphyxia
- Vitamin K deficiency

\section*{Investigations}
- Take blood for full blood count including a PBF
- Group and cross-match blood
- Coagulation screen

\section*{Normal values}

Prothrombin time (PT) is $12-13$ seconds and platelet count is $150-450 \times 10^{9} / \mathrm{L}$ as in adult. Babies who are not given vitamin K at birth will have a slightly prolonged PT in the first week Activated partial thromboplastin time (APPT) up to 3 wks $40-42 \mathrm{sec}$ in term \& up to 50 sec in preterm thereafter $28-39 \mathrm{sec}$ as in adult

\section*{Prevention}

All newborns should be given IM vitamin K Img at birth or soon after.
Prevent the predisposing factors
Interpretation of coagulation screen
Prolonged APPT alone: inherited individual factor deficiency
Prolonged PT alone/INR: vitamin K deficiency
Prolonged APPT \& PT: Liver disease
Prolonged APPT, PT \& low platelets (or prolonged PT \& low platelets): DIC

\section*{Management}
- Take history and examine baby, ensure warmth
- Investigate to identify causeTreat the cause immediately If from cord stump, retie or reclamplf cut press on bleeding site with sterile gauze
- Give vitamin $\mathrm{K} 1 \mathrm{mg} / \mathrm{kg}$ i.v even if the baby had already been given

