\section*{CORD INFECTION}

\section*{Definition}

Cord infection is inflammation of the umbilical stump usually occurring in the first week of life.
Often associated with inappropriate cord care application of saliva cow dung oil etc as unconventional methods to treat the cord.

\section*{Early signs}
- Redness at base of stump
- Wetness of Stump
- Offensive smell

\section*{Late Signs}
- Baby looks ill
- Temperature may be elevated
- Baby may refuse to feed
- Pus discharge from the umbilicus
- Jaundice

\section*{Management}
- Wash hands before handling the cord
- Wear clean gloves
- 7.1\% Chlorhexidine for cord care
- Keep cord dry
- Keep baby clean Continue breast feeding
- GiveAmoxicillin62.5gmg/kg-threetimesadayfor5days
- Admit baby with late signs
- Review baby after two days
- Refer or admit if pus or redness remains
- If improved continue antibiotic for 5days

\section*{Prevention}
- Clean hands
- Clean/sterile delivery instruments
- Clean surface
- Clean cutting of the cord Clean ligature
- Application of $7.1 \%$ chlorhexidine to cord
- Avoid application of harmful traditional substances (e.g. talcum powder, saliva, cow dung, etc)
- Educate mother on personal hygiene

