\section*{CONGENITAL SYPHILIS}

Occurs when a baby is born to an infected mother especially if inadequately treated during pregnancy.

Some infants with congenital syphilis have features of sepsis in neonatal period plus generalized rash that involves palms and soles, jaundice, hepatosplenomegaly, and limb pain/tenderness.

Undetected infection may develop late features of congenital syphilis with long term developmental complications.

\section*{Investigations}

VDRL \& confirmatory treponemal test, X-ray long bones, Bilirubin if needed, CSF- Serology

\section*{Treatment}

Benzyl penicillin for 10 days. A single dose of I.M Benzathine penicillin should be given for asymptomatic neonates with normal blood tests. Ensure the infected mother is fully treated and her sexual contacts are traced and treated. (Refer to national STI treatment guidelines)

\section*{HEPATITIS B INFECTION}

\section*{Risk factors}
- HepBsAg positive mothers
- High maternal hep B DNA viral load,

\section*{Prevention}

All babies born to mothers with above risk factors should be given hepatitis B vaccine at birth and if possible a dose of immunoglobulin $0.5 \mathrm{ml} / \mathrm{kg}$ IM. Follow up infant's HBsAg test should be done at 9 and 18 months.

Infected babies present with features of neonatal sepsis, and prolonged jaundice.

\section*{Investigation}
I. HepBsAg
2. Liver Function Tests: Enzymes, albumin, prothrombin time, bilirubin

\section*{OTHER INFECTIONS}
- Herpes simplex virus (HSV) \& Varicella
